(41, '3', 'SELECTED TOPICS/COMPUTER SCI: ST/ VULKAN', 'CS 419', 0, 'Topics of special and current interest not covered in other courses.', 'Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering or Pre-Engineering Program colleges.'),
(42, '4', 'SELECTED TOPICS/COMPUTER SCI: ST/DATA ANLTCS & APP MCH LRNG', 'CS 419', 0, 'Topics of special and current interest not covered in other courses.', ''),
(43, '3', 'SELECTED TOPICS/COMPUTER SCI: ST/VIRTUAL & AUGMENTED REALITY', 'CS 419', 0, 'Topics of special and current interest not covered in other courses.', ''),
(44, '3', 'GRAPH THEORY WITH APPLICATIONS TO COMPUTER SCIENCE', 'CS 420', 0, 'Directed and undirected graphs; paths, circuits, trees, coloring, planar graphs, partitioning; computer representation of graphs and graph algorithms; applications in software complexity metrics, program testing, and compiling.', 'Prerequisites: (CS 325 or 325H).A minimum grade of C is required in CS 325 and CS 325H.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(45, '4', 'CRYPTOGRAPHY', 'CS 427', 0, 'Introduction to the theory and practice of modern cryptography. Fundamental primitives including pseudorandom generators, block ciphers, hash functions. Symmetric-key cryptography for privacy and authenticity. Public-key cryptography based on number-theoretic problems.', 'Prerequisites: CS 261 or MTH 355.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 261 and MTH 355.Enrollment is limited to students with a major in Computer Science (307).Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(46, '4', 'MACHINE LEARNING AND DATA MINING', 'CS 434', 0, 'Introduction to machine learning and data mining algorithms (supervised learning, unsupervised learning, and reinforcement learning) tools that are widely employed in industrial and research settings.', 'Prerequisites: CS 325 or 325H.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 325 and CS 325H.Students cannot enroll who have a program in Computer Science Double Degree (297).Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(47, '4', 'DATABASE MANAGEMENT SYSTEMS', 'CS 440', 0, 'Relational database design, normalization, file structures, disk storage, query processing and optimization, team development of database applications.', 'Prerequisites: CS 261 and (CS 275 or 340).A minimum grade of C is required in CS 261, CS 275 and CS 340.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(48, '4', 'OPERATING SYSTEMS II', 'CS 444', 1, 'Principles of computer operating systems: concurrent processes, memory management, job scheduling, multiprocessing, file systems, performance evaluation, and networking. Lec/rec.', 'Prerequisites: (CS 311 or 344) and (CS 271 or ECE 375).A minimum grade of C is required in CS 311, CS 344, CS 271 and ECE 375.'),
(49, '3', 'NETWORKS IN COMPUTATIONAL BIOLOGY', 'CS 446', 0, 'An introduction to biological networks and computational methods for their analysis, inference, and functional modeling. Various network centralities, topological measures, clustering algorithms, and probabilistic annotation models are introduced in the context of protein interaction, gene regulatory, and metabolic networks. The course also surveys bioinformatics methods for data-driven inference of network structure.', 'Prerequisite: CS 261.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 261.'),
(50, '4', 'INTRODUCTION TO COMPUTER GRAPHICS', 'CS 450', 0, 'Theoretical and practical treatment of 3D computer graphics using OpenGL: geometric modeling, transformations, viewing, lighting, texture mapping, shading, rendering, and animation.', 'Prerequisites: CS 261 and (MTH 306, 306H or 341).A minimum grade of C is required in CS 261, MTH 306, MTH 306H and MTH 341.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(51, '4', 'SCIENTIFIC VISUALIZATION', 'CS 453', 0, 'Applies 3D computer graphics methods to visually understand scientific and engineering data. Methods include hyperbolic projections; mapping scalar values to color spaces; data visualization using range sliders; scalar visualization (point clouds, cutting planes, contour plots, isosurfaces); vector visualization (arrow clouds, particle advection, streamlines); terrain visualization; Delauney triangulation; and volume visualization.', ''),
(52, '4', 'COMPUTER GRAPHICS SHADERS', 'CS 457', 0, 'Theoretical and practical treatment of computer graphics shaders, including both RenderMan and GPU shaders. Programming in both RenderMan and OpenGL shading languages.', 'Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(53, '4', 'INTRODUCTION TO INFORMATION VISUALIZATION', 'CS 458', 0, 'Tools and techniques for designing, developing, and deploying interactive visualizations of abstract data sources. Discusses techniques based on principles from design, cognitive science, and perceptual psychology. Topics include 1D, 2D, 3D, multivariate representations, time-series, graphs and trees, text and documents, and interaction techniques.', 'Prerequisite: CS 361.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 361.'),
(54, '3', '^SENIOR SOFTWARE ENGIN PROJECT: SENIOR SOFTWARE ENGR PROJECT', 'CS 461', 1, 'Utilize software engineering methodology in a team environment to develop a real-world application. Teams will be responsible for all phases of software development, including project planning, requirements analysis, design, coding, testing, configuration management, quality assurance, documentation, and delivery. Three-term sequence required. This course fulfills the WIC requirement for computer science majors. (Writing Intensive Courses).', 'Prerequisite: CS 361.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 361.Students cannot enroll who have a program in Computer Science Double Degree (297).Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(55, '3', '^SENIOR SOFTWARE ENGINEERING PROJECT I', 'CS 461', 1, 'Utilize software engineering methodology in a team environment to develop a real-world application. Teams will be responsible for all phases of software development, including project planning, requirements analysis, design, coding, testing, configuration management, quality assurance, documentation, and delivery. Three-term sequence required. This course fulfills the WIC requirement for computer science majors. (Writing Intensive Courses).', 'Prerequisite: CS 361.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 361.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Computer Science (307).Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
(56, '3', '^SENIOR SOFTWARE ENGINEERING PROJECT II', 'CS 462', 1, 'Utilize software engineering methodology in a team environment to develop a real-world application. Teams will be responsible for all phases of software development, including project planning, requirements analysis, design, coding, testing, configuration management, quality assurance, documentation, and delivery. Three-term sequence required. (Writing Intensive Courses)', 'Prerequisites: CS 362 and 461.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 362 and CS 461.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(57, '2', 'SENIOR SOFTWARE ENGINEERING PROJECT', 'CS 463', 1, 'Utilize software engineering methodology in a team environment to develop a real-world application. Teams will be responsible for all phases of software development, including project planning, requirements analysis, design, coding, testing, configuration management, quality assurance, documentation, and delivery. Three-term sequence required.', 'Prerequisite: CS 462.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 462.Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
(58, '2', 'SOFTWARE ENGINEERING PROJECT: ST/ SENIOR SOFTWARE ENGR PROJ', 'CS 463', 1, 'Utilize software engineering methodology in a team environment to develop a real-world application. Teams will be responsible for all phases of software development, including project planning, requirements analysis, design, coding, testing, configuration management, quality assurance, documentation, and delivery. Three-term sequence required.', 'Prerequisite: CS 462.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 462.Students cannot enroll who have a program in Computer Science Double Degree (297).Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(59, '4', 'OPEN SOURCE SOFTWARE', 'CS 464', 0, 'Provides a theoretical foundation of the history, key concepts, technologies, and practices associated with modern Free and Open Source Software (FOSS) projects, and gives students an opportunity to explore and make contributions to FOSS projects with some mentoring and guidance.', 'Prerequisites: CS 261 or 361.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 261 and CS 361.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Elect & Computer Engineering (039), Computer Science (249), Computer Science Double Degree (297) or Computer Science (307).Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(60, '4', 'WEB-BASED START-UP PROJECT', 'CS 466', 0, 'Real-world, hands-on learning in a high-tech web/mobile-based company environment. Research in the development of product ideas, hypotheses, and business models to create customer experiments. Prototyping and statistical analysis to develop, optimize, and evaluate solutions. Rapid iteration/refactoring based on customer input, web analytics, and user engagement metrics. Offered at OSU-Cascades only.', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Computer Science (307).Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
(61, '4', 'ONLINE CAPSTONE PROJECT', 'CS 467', 0, 'Real-world team-based experience with the software engineering design and delivery cycle, including requirements analysis and specification, design techniques, and requirements and final project written documentation. For students in the online CS double-degree program only.', 'Prerequisites: CS 344, 361 and 362.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 344, CS 361 and CS 362.Enrollment is limited to Postbac Degree Seeking level students.Enrollment limited to students in the Dist. Degree Corvallis Student campus.'),
(62, '4', 'INCLUSIVE DESIGN (HCI)', 'CS 468', 0, 'Inclusive design is designing software that works for a wide variety of differently abled customers. Teaches the skills needed to design inclusively without having to have a separate design for each differently abled customer.', 'Prerequisite: CS 352.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 352.'),
(63, '4', 'COMPUTER ARCHITECTURE', 'CS 472', 0, 'Computer architecture using processors, memories, and I/O devices as building blocks. Issues involved in the design of instruction set architecture, processor, pipelining and memory organization. Design philosophies and trade-offs involved in Reduced Instruction Set Computer (RISC) architectures. Lec/lab. CROSSLISTED as CS 472/ECE 472 and CS 572/ECE 572.', 'Prerequisite: ECE 375.A minimum grade of C is required in ECE 375.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(64, '4', 'INTRODUCTION TO PARALLEL PROGRAMMING', 'CS 475', 0, 'Theoretical and practical survey of parallel programming, including a discussion of parallel architectures, parallel programming paradigms, and parallel algorithms. Programming one or more parallel computers in a higher-level parallel language.', 'Prerequisite: CS 261.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 261.Students cannot enroll who have a program in Computer Science Double Degree (297).Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(65, '4', 'ADVANCED COMPUTER NETWORKING', 'CS 476', 0, 'Advanced networking concepts: source/channel coding, queuing theory, router design, network architectures (Intserv, DiffServ, MPLS), multimedia protocols (TFRC, RTP), overlay networks, and wireless standards (Bluetooth 802.11b, 3/4G). CROSSLISTED as CS 476/ECE 476 and CS 576/ECE 576.', 'Prerequisites: (CS 372 or ECE 372) and (ECE 353, ST 314 or 314H).A minimum grade of C is required in CS 372, ECE 372, ECE 353, ST 314 and ST 314H.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(66, '4', 'INTRODUCTION TO DIGITAL FORENSICS', 'CS 477', 0, 'Introduces concepts related to digital forensics, its role and importance, and tools and techniques for collecting and curating digital evidence. The course will also discuss the role of evidence in the justice system and some legal aspects as they pertain to digital forensics. It will introduce tools and techniques for computer and network forensics.', 'Prerequisites: CS 344 and 370.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 344 and CS 370.'),
(67, '4', 'NETWORK SECURITY', 'CS 478', 0, 'Basic concepts and techniques in network security, risks and vulnerabilities, applied cryptography and various network security protocols. Coverage of high-level concepts such as authentication, confidentiality, integrity, and availability applied to networking systems. Fundamental techniques including authentication protocols, group key establishment and management, trusted intermediaries, public key infrastructures, SSL/TLS, IPSec, firewalls and intrusion detection CROSSLISTED as CS 478/ECE 478.', 'Prerequisites: CS 372 or ECE 372.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 372 and ECE 372.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(68, '4', 'TRANSLATORS', 'CS 480', 0, 'An introduction to compilers; attribute grammars, syntax-directed translation, lex, yacc, LR(1) parsers, symbol tables, semantic analysis, and peep-hole optimization.', 'Prerequisites: (CS 344 or 311) and CS 321.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 344, CS 311 and CS 321.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(69, '4', 'COMPUTER SCIENCE SKILLS FOR SIMULATION AND GAME PROGRAMMING', 'CS 491', 0, 'Game and simulation development is very much a data and math-intensive activity. A certain number of actions must be produced, and producing them by hand is hard. This is a middleware CS course that fills in many of the missing pieces for those wanting to enter the simulation and game development worlds in a software tool-building capacity.', 'Prerequisites: CS 261 and (CS 225 or MTH 231) and MTH 252.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 261, CS 225, MTH 231 and MTH 252.'),
(70, '4', 'MOBILE SOFTWARE DEVELOPMENT', 'CS 492', 0, 'Introduction to concepts and techniques for developing mobile applications. Students will become familiar with modern mobile structure, implementation, development tools, and workflow.', 'Prerequisite: CS 344.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 344.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Computer Science (307).Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
(71, '4', 'CLOUD APPLICATION DEVELOPMENT', 'CS 493', 0, 'Covers developing RESTful cloud services, an approach based on representational state transfer technology, an architectural style and approach to communications used in modern cloud services development.', 'Prerequisites: CS 290, 340 and 372.A minimum grade of C is required in CS 290, CS 340 and CS 372.'),
(72, '3', 'SPECIAL TOPICS: ST/ CYBER-PHYSICAL SYSTEMS', 'CS 499', 0, '', 'Enrollment limited to students with a term level of Junior or Senior.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
