(327, '4', 'TOPICS IN AMERICAN STUDIES', 'AMS 311', 0, 'Selected topics, changed annually, that investigate American ideas, regions, events, or periods. Fulfills the requirement for an integrated course in the major. May be repeated as topics vary. Open to nonmajors.', 'Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
(328, '1 to 16', 'READING AND CONFERENCE', 'AMS 405', 0, 'Independent, individual studies supervised by the director, members of the American Studies Board, or assigned professors, as arranged by the student and the director.', 'Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
(329, '1 to 16', 'PROJECTS', 'AMS 406', 0, 'Studies of American culture and society centered around topical events or cultural programs of current interest in American studies.', 'Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
(330, '1', 'ORIENTATION TO ANIMAL AND RANGELAND SCIENCES', 'ANS 100', 0, 'Designed to provide incoming Animal and Rangeland Sciences students an introduction to college life at OSU with an emphasis on the faculty, facilities, services, and the curricula of the Department of Animal and Rangeland Sciences.', ''),
(331, '4', '*INTRODUCTION TO ANIMAL SCIENCES', 'ANS 121', 0, 'Principles of breeding, physiology, nutrition, and management as they apply to modern livestock and poultry production. Lec/lab. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(332, '2', 'SOPHOMORE SEMINAR', 'ANS 207', 0, 'Examination of career opportunities in animal sciences.', ''),
(333, '3', 'BEEF/DAIRY INDUSTRIES', 'ANS 215', 0, 'Introduction to beef and dairy industries; history, current industry status, and demonstration and practice of basic husbandry skills.', ''),
(334, '3', 'SMALL RUMINANT/SWINE INDUSTRIES', 'ANS 216', 0, 'Introduction to the small ruminant and swine industries including history, current status and production practices, with demonstration and hands-on experience of basic husbandry practices.', ''),
(335, '3', 'POULTRY INDUSTRIES', 'ANS 217', 0, 'Familiarization of the organizational structure and marketing arrangement of poultry industries; hands-on managerial techniques, practices and procedures carried out by the poultry industries.', ''),
(336, '3', 'INTRODUCTORY HORSE SCIENCE', 'ANS 220', 0, 'Introduction to horses, their history, breeds, form and function, performance evaluation, current industry status, and general management.', ''),
(337, '3', 'LIVESTOCK EVALUATION', 'ANS 231', 0, 'Focuses on an individual animal\'s economic merit as compared to a sample group. Visual appraisal, performance data, and carcass merit are stressed. Includes the evaluation of both market and breeding animals. The livestock species of concentration include beef cattle, swine, sheep, and meat goats. Lec/lab.', ''),
(338, '3', 'PRINCIPLES OF ANIMAL FOODS TECHNOLOGY', 'ANS 251', 0, 'Processing of meat, milk and eggs into human food products. Lec/lab.', ''),
(339, '4', 'COMPANION ANIMAL MANAGEMENT', 'ANS 280', 0, 'An introduction to the challenges, responsibilities, and benefits of interaction with selected companion animals. Topics covered will provide an overview of the human-animal bond, the position of companion animals in society, ethical issues of pet ownership and potential career opportunities. In addition, the course will serve as an introduction to preventive care and normal behavior of dogs, cats, and selected exotic pets. As the Department of Animal and Rangeland Sciences curriculum offers courses addressing equine care and husbandry, horses will not be discussed in this class.', ''),
(340, '4', 'COMMON DISEASES OF COMPANION ANIMALS', 'ANS 302', 0, 'An introduction to common diseases of selected companion animals. Emphasis will be placed on identifying predisposing factors, clinical signs, common diagnostic procedures and potential implications for human health. A $10 course fee will be required. Lec/rec.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H) and CH 121, 122 and 123.A minimum grade of D- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213, BI 213H, CH 121, CH 122 and CH 123.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.'),
(341, '3', 'PRINCIPLES OF ANIMAL NUTRITION', 'ANS 311', 0, 'Classification, digestion, absorption, and metabolism of nutrients in animals; consequences of nutritional deficiencies and toxicities.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H).A minimum grade of D- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212 and BI 212H.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.'),
(342, '4', 'APPLIED ANIMAL NUTRITION: FEEDS AND RATION FORMULATION', 'ANS 313', 0, 'Discusses topics relevant to feedstuff identification and nutrient analysis, feed processing and formulation of balanced animal diets based on nutrient requirements. Provides students hands-on experiences in identifying various feedstuffs and formulating rations based on the nutrient composition of those feedstuffs. Also offered at EOU and through Ecampus.', ''),
(343, '4', 'ANIMAL PHYSIOLOGY', 'ANS 314', 0, 'Biological basis of animal performance; describes how networks of cells act cooperatively to enable locomotion, provide a stable internal environment, allocate resources, remove metabolic end-products, and counteract microorganisms.', ''),
(344, '3', '*CONTENTIOUS SOCIAL ISSUES IN ANIMAL AGRICULTURE', 'ANS 315', 0, 'Discussion of contentious issues including role of animal products and human health; use of hormones and antibiotics; new animal biotechnologies; animal rights/welfare; livestock grazing on public lands. (Bacc Core Course).', 'Enrollment limited to students in the LaGrande/EOU campus.'),
(345, '4', 'REPRODUCTION IN DOMESTIC ANIMALS', 'ANS 316', 0, 'Anatomy and physiology of mammalian and avian reproductive systems; fertilization, embryonic and fetal development, placentation and parturition; reproductive technologies. Lec/rec.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 211 or 211H) and (CH 121, 221, 231 or 231H).A minimum grade of D- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, CH 121, CH 221, CH 231 and CH 231H.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.'),
(346, '1', 'REPRODUCTION IN DOMESTIC ANIMALS LABORATORY', 'ANS 317', 0, 'Gross and microscopic anatomy of the reproductive tract; semen collection, evaluation and extension; evaluation of fertilization, embryo and fetal development and placentation. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisite: ANS 316*.* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of D- is required in ANS 316.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
(347, '3', 'PRINCIPLES OF COMPANION ANIMAL NUTRITION', 'ANS 320', 0, 'Learn about nutrients, the digestive process, and the application of nutritional sciences to the health and welfare of companion animals. Introduction to the metabolic basis and practical preventative management for nutritional diseases in companion animals.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H).A minimum grade of D- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212 and BI 212H.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.'),
(348, '3', 'EQUINE STABLE MANAGEMENT', 'ANS 333', 0, 'Discusses developing a business plan, financial statements, and ratios, budgeting, financial planning, taxation, and employment issues within the current equine industry.', 'Prerequisite: ANS 220.A minimum grade of D- is required in ANS 220.'),
(349, '3', 'EQUINE HEALTH AND DISEASE', 'ANS 335', 0, 'Recognition of common diseases and disorders including their cause, treatment and prevention. Management of internal and external parasites. Recognizing common lameness issues.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.'),
(350, '3', 'ANIMAL BEHAVIOR AND COGNITION', 'ANS 341', 0, 'Survey, discuss, and explore principles of animal behavior and cognition from a comparative perspective, taking into account the interacting influences of biology, environment, and life experience on the individual and group behavior of animals across species. Aspects of animal cognition, including reasoning, perception, memory and personality, that play an important role in animal behavior will also be addressed.', 'Prerequisites: BI 102 or 213.A minimum grade of D is required in BI 102 and BI 213.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
(351, '4', 'ADVANCED PRINCIPLES OF ANIMAL FOODS TECHNOLOGY', 'ANS 351', 0, 'Provides in-depth coverage of both fresh and processed meats and eggs into products suitable for human consumption.', ''),
(352, '4', 'ANIMAL GENETICS', 'ANS 378', 0, 'Fundamentals of inheritance, principles of genetic segregation, population and quantitative genetics, response to natural selection and artificial manipulation of populations.', 'Prerequisites: BI 211, 212 or 213.A minimum grade of D- is required in BI 211, BI 212 and BI 213.'),
(353, '3', 'PRINCIPLES OF ANIMAL ANATOMY AND PHYSIOLOGY', 'ANS 380', 0, 'An introductory course in animal anatomy to provide a foundation for advanced courses in the Animal Science curriculum. Emphasis is on acquisition of a basic knowledge of minute and gross anatomical structures, their operation, and integration. Begins with anatomical nomenclature such as body planes and directional terms then covers the following tissues and organ systems: epithelium, connective tissue, blood and bone marrow, bone/cartilage, muscle tissue, nervous tissue, digestive system, circulatory system, reproductive system, urinary system, and respiratory system.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H).A minimum grade of D is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213 and BI 213H.'),
(354, '3', 'FOUNDATIONS OF MAMMALIAN HISTOLOGY', 'ANS 385', 0, 'Provides a basic knowledge of mammalian microscopic anatomy. Emphasis will be on the appearance, organization and function of minute anatomical structures that can only be observed with the help of a visual enhancer, such as a microscope. Covers basic histological techniques and histology and related functions of the following tissues and organ systems: epithelium, connective tissue, bone/cartilage, blood, muscle tissue, nervous tissue, circulatory system, digestive system, reproductive system, urinary system, respiratory system, immune system, integument, eye and ear. Also covers gametogenesis, fertilization, and early development of the vertebrate embryo. Lec/rec.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H) and (BI 314 or 314H).A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213, BI 213H, BI 314 and BI 314H.'),
(355, '4', 'GROSS ANATOMY OF DOMESTIC ANIMALS', 'ANS 390', 0, 'Provides a foundation for advanced courses in the Animal Sciences curriculum. Emphasis on gaining knowledge of mammalian anatomy. Lectures cover anatomical nomenclature, structure, operation, and integration of major organ systems. The dog is used as the general model while comparative domestic animal anatomy is also covered. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H).A minimum grade of D is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213 and BI 213H.'),
