(980, '4', '*ENVIRONMENTAL BIOLOGY: ECOLOGY, CONSERVATION, GLOBAL CHANGE', 'BI 101', 0, 'Introduction to ecosystems, including biodiversity, species interactions, human impacts, and conservation biology. Lectures introduce biological themes and research in the context of current issues in science and society. Hands-on laboratories focus on using organisms and technologies to explore biology and develop skills for lifelong learning. No previous science courses are required, intended for non-biological science majors. This course can be taken alone or in any combination with BI 102 or 103. Lec/lab/rec. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(981, '4', '*ANIMAL BIOLOGY: GENES, BEHAVIOR AND EVOLUTION OF LIFE', 'BI 102', 0, 'Introduction to how genetics shapes life on Earth, including how understandings of DNA and environmental factors are leading to biotechnological advances. Lectures introduce biological themes and research in the context of current issues in science and society. Hands-on laboratories focus on using organisms and technologies to explore biology and develop skills for lifelong learning. No previous science courses are required, intended for non-biological science majors. This course can be taken alone or in any combination with BI 101 and BI 103. Lec/lab/rec. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(982, '4', '*HUMAN BIOLOGY: ANATOMY, PHYSIOLOGY AND DISEASE', 'BI 103', 0, 'Introduction to the biology of humans, including aspects of human health and disease. Lectures introduce biological themes and research in the context of current issues in science and society. Hands-on laboratories focus on using organisms and technologies to explore biology and develop skills for lifelong learning. No previous science courses are required, intended for non-biological science majors. This course can be taken alone or in any combination with BI 101 and BI 102. Lec/lab/rec. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(983, '1', 'HEALTH PROFESSIONS: MEDICAL', 'BI 109', 0, 'Discussion of matters relating to a medical career. Includes application procedures, the importance of various requirements, admissions, professional school curricula, financing education, and related matters. Speakers are included. Graded P/N.', 'Enrollment limited to students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore, Junior or Senior.'),
(984, '1', 'INTRODUCTION TO MARINE LIFE IN THE SEA: MARINE HABITATS', 'BI 111', 0, 'A field-focused learning experience exploring the varied marine life and habitats on the Oregon coast, including rocky shores, sandy beaches, mud flats, bays and estuaries. Students will also be introduced to the breadth of marine science course offerings and research at Oregon State University?s Hatfield Marine Science Center located in Newport, Oregon. Graded P/N.', ''),
(985, '3', 'INTRODUCTION TO MARINE BIOLOGY', 'BI 150', 0, 'Survey of marine organisms, the environments they inhabit, and their evolutionary adaptations for thriving in those environments. The course will also highlight current conservation challenges that threaten marine life, such as climate change, overfishing, and pollution.', ''),
(986, '3', '*GENOMES, IDENTITIES AND SOCIETIES', 'BI 175', 0, 'DNA\'s roles in shaping our senses of identity, individuality, and societal interconnectivity will be analyzed. New advances in genetic technology will be explored, along with their potential impacts on society. The relationships between genetics and discrimination will be examined with focus on cases from Oregon, America, and the world. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(987, '1', 'PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT I: HEALTH PROFESSIONS', 'BI 197', 0, 'Integrative Biology faculty and other professionals introduce a variety of human health professions including dentistry, medicine, pharmacy and others (veterinary medicine students take BI 198). Emphasizes professional development through exploring relevant social and cognitive concepts, as well as engaging in experiential learning and networking. Departmental and campus student success resources are highlighted. Graded P/N.', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Non-Degree Science (499), Biology (509) or University Exploratory Studies (800).'),
(988, '1', 'PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT I: BIOLOGY AND ZOOLOGY', 'BI 198', 0, 'Integrative Biology faculty and biology professionals introduce life science careers outside of human health professions (human health profession students take BI 197). Emphasizes professional development through exploring relevant social and cognitive concepts, as well as engaging in experiential learning and networking. Departmental and campus student success resources are highlighted. Graded P/N.', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Non-Degree Science (499)Biology (509)Zoology (620)Undecided Science Major (640)University Exploratory Studies (800)'),
(989, '4', '*INTRODUCTORY BIOLOGY I', 'BI 204', 0, 'Foundations of biological sciences including scientific inquiry, genetics, evolution, and ecology. Significant emphasis throughout on the application of core concepts to solve human and environmental problems. Laboratory emphasizes skills in critical thinking, scientific writing, and experimental design. Not intended for pre-health profession students. Lec/lab. (Bacc Core Course)', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Crop and Soil Science (120)Fisheries and Wildlife Science (133)General Agriculture (140)Horticulture (145)Environmental Econ and Policy (237)Agricultural Sciences (259)Rangeland Sciences (292)Computer Science (307)Pre-Computer Science (335)Biology (509)Botany (515)Environmental Science (542)Zoology (620)Natural Resources (643)Environmental Sciences (657)Natural Resources (671)Fisheries & Wildlife Sciences (733)Anthropology (860)Sustainability (870)Psychology (965)Enrollment limited to students in the Dist. Degree Corvallis Student or LaGrande/EOU campuses.'),
(990, '4', '*INTRODUCTORY BIOLOGY II', 'BI 205', 0, 'Fundamental concepts in molecular and cellular biology, beginning with biomolecules and the origin of life, and ending with genomics. Significant emphasis throughout on applications of biotechnology to solve human problems. Laboratory emphasizes skills in critical thinking, scientific writing, and experimental design. Not intended for pre-health profession students. Lec/lab. (Bacc Core Course)', 'Prerequisites: CH 121* or 201* or ((CH 231* or 231H*) and (CH 261*, 261H*, 271* or 271H*)).* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of D- is required in CH 121, CH 201, CH 231, CH 231H, CH 261, CH 261H, CH 271 and CH 271H.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Crop and Soil Science (120)Fisheries and Wildlife Science (133)General Agriculture (140)Horticulture (145)Environmental Econ and Policy (237)Agricultural Sciences (259)Rangeland Sciences (292)Computer Science (307)Pre-Computer Science (335)Biology (509)Botany (515)Environmental Science (542)Zoology (620)Natural Resources (643)Environmental Sciences (657)Natural Resources (671)Fisheries & Wildlife Sciences (733)Anthropology (860)Sustainability (870)Psychology (965)Enrollment limited to students in the Dist. Degree Corvallis Student or LaGrande/EOU campuses.'),
(991, '4', '*INTRODUCTORY BIOLOGY III', 'BI 206', 0, 'Basic plant and animal physiology from an evolutionary perspective. Significant emphasis on topics of importance to human society, including human and plant disease. Laboratory emphasizes skills in critical thinking, scientific writing, and experimental design. Not intended for pre-health professional students. Lec/lab. (Bacc Core Course)', 'Prerequisites: CH 121* or 201* or ((CH 231* or 231H*) and (CH 261*, 261H*, 271* or 271H*)).* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of D- is required in CH 121, CH 201, CH 231, CH 231H, CH 261, CH 261H, CH 271 and CH 271H.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Crop and Soil Science (120)Fisheries and Wildlife Science (133)General Agriculture (140)Horticulture (145)Environmental Econ and Policy (237)Agricultural Sciences (259)Rangeland Sciences (292)Computer Science (307)Pre-Computer Science (335)Biology (509)Botany (515)Environmental Science (542)Zoology (620)Natural Resources (643)Environmental Sciences (657)Natural Resources (671)Fisheries & Wildlife Sciences (733)Anthropology (860)Sustainability (870)Psychology (965)Enrollment limited to students in the Dist. Degree Corvallis Student or LaGrande/EOU campuses.'),
(992, '4', '*PRINCIPLES OF BIOLOGY', 'BI 211', 0, 'Origins of life, energy transformations, plant and animal diversity. Lec/lab. (Bacc Core Course)', 'Students in the College of Business, College of Liberal Arts or Pre-Business Program colleges may not enroll.'),
(993, '3', 'INTRODUCTION TO HUMAN ANATOMY AND PHYSIOLOGY', 'BI 231', 0, 'The first of a three-term introductory series. Using a strong gross anatomy focus, course topics address fundamental concepts of biology as they apply to human anatomy and physiology and then focus on understanding the structures, functions, and regulatory mechanisms involved in the human skeleton, muscular and integumentary systems. BI 231 is a required prerequisite to BI 232 and BI 233. The BI 241 Lab is optional but prerequisite for either of the subsequent BI 242 or BI 243 lab courses in the series. Lec.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
(994, '2', 'INTRODUCTION TO HUMAN ANATOMY AND PHYSIOLOGY LABORATORY', 'BI 241', 0, 'The first of a three-term introductory series. Using the human cadaver (prosection), course topics address fundamental concepts of biology as they apply to human anatomy and physiology and then focus on understanding the structures, functions, and regulatory mechanisms involved in the human skeletal, muscular and integumentary systems. Physiology demonstrations illustrate functions of organ systems. Lab/rec.', 'Prerequisite: BI 231*.* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 231.'),
(995, '1', 'PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT FOR BIOLOGISTS II', 'BI 298', 0, 'Students will develop awareness of the elements of professional development, identify strategic areas for growth, and design an exploration plan. Emphasis is placed on being able to analyze career opportunities to determine the best mix of technical and professional skills needed for success as a biological science professional. Graded P/N.', ''),
(996, '3', '*HUMAN IMPACTS ON ECOSYSTEMS', 'BI 301', 0, 'Selected human impacts on ecosystems are examined in depth, including air quality, global climate change, management of agricultural and forest resources, and threats to biological diversity. The causes, approaches to investigating, and potential solutions for each issue are discussed from a scientific and social perspective. Adverse effects on ecosystems that result from each environmental problem are examined. (Bacc Core Course)', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
(997, '3', '*^ENVIRONMENTAL ECOLOGY', 'BI 306H', 0, 'Biological, physical, and chemical nature of both natural and human-disturbed ecosystems. Topics include population and conservation ecology, toxins in the food chain and in the environment, forest decline and acid rain, eutrophication of terrestrial and aquatic ecosystems, and ecosystem restoration. Offered alternate years. (Bacc Core Course) (Writing Intensive Course)', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment limited to students in a Honors Bachelor of Arts, Honors Bachelor of Fine Arts or Honors Bachelor of Science degrees.'),
(998, '1 to 6', 'TEACHING PRACTICUM', 'BI 309', 0, 'Introductory experience for students assisting with instruction in Biology or Zoology courses. Admission is by application. See Cordley 3029 for details.', ''),
(999, '4', 'GENETICS', 'BI 311', 0, 'Fundamentals of Mendelian, quantitative, population, molecular, and developmental genetics. Lec/rec.', 'Prerequisites: ((BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H)) or (BI 204, 205 and 206).A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213, BI 213H, BI 204, BI 205 and BI 206.'),
(1000, '3', 'MOLECULAR BIOLOGY LABORATORY', 'BI 315', 0, 'Laboratory projects exploring the transmission of genetic information from storage to function will introduce students to fundamental molecular biology concepts and techniques, including isolation of DNA, construction of recombinant plasmids, quantification of gene expression in model organisms, polymerase chain reaction, and analysis of protein expression and subcellalar localization. Lec/lab. CROSSLISTED as BB 315/BI 315.', 'Prerequisites: BB 314* or 314H*.* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of C- is required in BB 314 and BB 314H.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Genetics (517).'),
(1001, '3', '^SCIENTIFIC THEORY AND PRACTICE', 'BI 317', 0, 'Teaches students the practice of biological science. Topics cover scientific theory, communications, ethics and critical evaluation. CROSSLISTED as BB 317/BI 317. (Writing Intensive Course)', 'Prerequisites: (BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H).A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213 and BI 213H.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Biology (509).'),
(1002, '3', '^THEORY, PRACTICE AND DISCOURSE IN THE LIFE SCIENCES', 'BI 319', 0, 'The practice of science and the critical evaluation of scientific claims are explored though writings, discussions and presentations. Topics including the scientific method, ethics and the role of science in society are examined along with implications for professionals ranging from health care to environmental biology. Strategies for effectively communicating science with diverse audiences are emphasized. (Writing Intensive Course).', 'Prerequisites: ((BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H)) and (ST 351 or 351H).A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213 and BI 213H.A minimum grade of D- is required in ST 351 and ST 351H.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Biology (509) or Zoology (620).'),
(1003, '3', '^THINKING & COMM LIFE SCIENCE', 'BI 319', 0, 'Teaches students the practice of biological science. Topics cover scientific theory, written and spoken communications, ethics and critical evaluation. (Writing Intensive Course) CROSSLISTED as Z 319.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H) and (ST 351 or 351H) and ST 352*.* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213 and BI 213H.A minimum grade of D- is required in ST 351, ST 351H and ST 352.Enrollment is limited to students with a major in Biology (509) or Zoology (620).'),
(1004, '3', 'ADVANCED HUMAN ANATOMY AND PHYSIOLOGY', 'BI 331', 0, 'The first of a three-term advanced series. With a strong focus on the physiological underpinnings of disease, course topics address the fundamental concepts of human anatomy and physiology and then focus on understanding the structures, functions, regulatory mechanisms and common pathologies involved in the skeletal, muscular and integumentary systems. Lec.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H) and (CH 123 or ((CH 233 or 233H) and (CH 263 or 263H))) and BI 341*.* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213, BI 213H, CH 123, CH 233, CH 233H, CH 263, CH 263H and BI 341.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.'),
(1005, '2', 'ADVANCED HUMAN ANATOMY AND PHYSIOLOGY LABORATORY', 'BI 341', 0, 'The first of a three-term advanced series. Using the human cadaver (prosection) and physiological data acquisition equipment, course topics address the fundamental concepts of human anatomy and physiology and then focus on understanding the structures, functions, regulatory mechanisms and common pathologies involved in the human skeletal, muscular and integumentary systems. Lab.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.'),
(1006, '3', '*INTRODUCTION TO EVOLUTION', 'BI 345', 0, 'Elements of evolutionary theory; origin and history of life; evolutionary controversy; origins of species, sex, and humans. (Bacc Core Course)', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
(1007, '3', '*OCEANS IN PERIL', 'BI 347', 0, 'The interactions of society and the marine environment, emphasizing the ecological, biogeochemical, economic, sociological, and political significance of the oceans. Topics of current critical importance will include marine pollution, protecting marine habitats, conserving marine biodiversity, fisheries and aquaculture, ocean energy, biogeochemical change, global warming, ocean acidification, and sea level rise. Lecture (Bacc Core Course).', 'Prerequisites: BI 101, 102, 211, 211H, 213, 213H, 204 or 150.A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 101, BI 102, BI 211, BI 211H, BI 213, BI 213H, BI 204 and BI 150.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
(1008, '3', 'MARINE ECOLOGY', 'BI 351', 0, 'Ecological interactions and principles in different marine habitats. Topics include the organisms (plants, invertebrates, vertebrates) found in major habitats and interactions between organisms. Habitats discussed include coral reefs, rocky shores, kelp forests, near-shore waters, open-ocean waters, and the deep sea. Emphasis is placed on how organism-organism interactions produce varying patterns of distribution, abundance, body size, diversity, stability, and succession.', 'Prerequisites: ((BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H)) or (BI 204, 205 and 206).A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213, BI 213H, BI 204, BI 205 and BI 206.'),
(1009, '4', 'PACIFIC NORTHWEST COASTAL ECOSYSTEMS', 'BI 353', 0, 'A field-based introduction to the diversity of ecosystems of the Pacific Northwest coast. Biological and physical processes affecting the distribution, structure, community composition and physical features of these systems are explored through a variety of lectures and field trips. Ecosystem services and human impacts are examined.', 'Prerequisites: ((BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H)) or (BI 204, 205 and 206).A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213, BI 213H, BI 204, BI 205 and BI 206.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
(1010, '3', 'SYMBIOSES AND THE ENVIRONMENT', 'BI 358', 0, 'Overview of the diversity of mutualistic symbioses and their roles in the natural environment. Integrative approach, from ecosystem to molecule, to the examination of certain key mutualisms. Lec. Offered alternate years.', 'Prerequisites: (((BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H)) or (BI 204, 205 and 206)) and (CH 123 or (CH 233 or 233H) and (CH 263 or 263H)).A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213, BI 213H, BI 204, BI 205, BI 206, CH 123, CH 233, CH 233H, CH 263 and CH 263H.'),
(1011, '3', 'ECOLOGY', 'BI 370', 0, 'The study of interactions between organisms and their biotic and abiotic environments at the population, community, ecosystem, and biosphere levels of organization.', 'Prerequisites: ((BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H)) or (BI 204, 205 and 206).A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213, BI 213H, BI 204, BI 205 and BI 206.'),
(1012, '3', '^ECOLOGICAL METHODS', 'BI 371', 0, 'Experimental design, data collection, analysis and synthesis in ecological studies; local ecosystems emphasized. May have field trip fee. Lec/lab. (Writing Intensive Course)', 'Prerequisites: BI 370 or 370H.A minimum grade of D- is required in BI 370 and BI 370H.Enrollment is limited to students with a major in Biology (509), Botany (515) or Zoology (620).'),
(1013, '3', '^FIELD METHODS IN MARINE ECOLOGY', 'BI 373', 0, 'Exposure to research methods used in field studies of the marine rocky intertidal ecosystem. Research projects and writing exercises provide students with hands-on experience of collecting, analyzing, and presenting marine ecological data. Field trip fee. Lab fee. Lec/lab. (Writing Intensive Course)', 'Prerequisites: (BI 351*, 370 or 370H) and (ST 351 or 351H).* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of D- is required in BI 351, BI 370, BI 370H, ST 351 and ST 351H.'),
(1014, '4', 'FIELD METHODS IN ECOLOGICAL RESTORATION', 'BI 375', 0, 'Observation and application of theory and practice in ecological restoration. Using site visits and hands-on research, explores the roles in restoration of fire, local adaptation, disturbance history, natural history, beaver, and soils, including visits to several active and completed restoration projects and overnights in the field. Lab.', 'Prerequisites: ((BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H)) or (BI 204, 205 and 206).A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213, BI 213H, BI 204, BI 205 and BI 206.Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
(1015, '1 to 16', 'RESEARCH AND SCHOLARSHIP', 'BI 401', 0, '', ''),
(1016, '1', 'RESEARCH AND SCHOLARSHIP: Beaver Dam Analog Monitoring', 'BI 401', 0, '', 'Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
(1017, '1 to 16', 'RESEARCH AND SCHOLARSHIP: RESEARCH & SCHOLARSHIP', 'BI 401', 0, '', ''),
(1018, '2', 'RESEARCH AND SCHOLARSHIP: Software Dev Native Plant ID', 'BI 401', 0, '', 'Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
