(1115, '6', 'BUSINESS NOW', 'BA 101', 0, 'Presents an integrated view of both established and entrepreneurial business organizations by studying their common processes and characteristics. Introduces theory and develops basic skills in the areas of management, finance, accounting and marketing. Lec/lab/rec.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Management (196)Apparel Design (400)Merchandising Management (416)Pre-Apparel (453)Pre-Interiors (454)Interior Design (458)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)University Exploratory Studies (800)Design & Innovation Management (912)'),
(1116, '2', 'FINANCIAL LITERACY FOR COLLEGE LIFE', 'BA 140', 0, 'Helps you learn the fundamentals of personal finance. It is crucial you are prepared to be prudent managers of your financial resources, enabling you to achieve long- and short-term financial goals and security. In addition, this course will examine how your background experiences, values, goals, and decisions can impact your financial future.', 'Students in the College of Business college may not enroll.'),
(1117, '3', 'B-ENGAGED', 'BA 160', 0, 'Understand and accomplish college-level academic work and explore OSU resources and options that will enhance your college experience and success. Opportunity to connect with faculty and peers with common interests in a supportive learning environment.', 'Enrollment limited to students with a term level of Freshman.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Business college.'),
(1118, '3', 'INNOVATION NATION--AWARENESS TO ACTION', 'BA 161', 0, 'First course in a two-course sequence. Begins a conversation on self-management, offering opportunities for active reflection on critical skill sets necessary for success in today\'s global market. Builds a foundation of entrepreneurial knowledge and gaining a competitive edge while becoming aware of your role in managing your own career.', 'Enrollment limited to students with a term level of Freshman.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Business college.'),
(1119, '3', 'INNOVATION NATION--IDEAS TO REALITY', 'BA 162', 0, 'Second course in a two-course sequence. Topics include evaluating entrepreneurial capabilities, creativity and innovation, opportunity recognition, impression management, and responsible business practices. Continues a conversation on self-management, offering opportunities for active reflection on critical skill sets necessary for success in today\'s global market.', 'Prerequisites: BA 161 or 161H.A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 161 and BA 161H.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Business college.'),
(1120, '3', 'B-ENGAGED', 'BA 163', 0, 'The first term is a critical time for college students. B-Engaged helps the student transition to the OSU academic community and college learning expectations. B-Engaged will help the student understand and accomplish college-level academic work and explore OSU resources and options that will enhance their college experience and success. Additionally, B-Engaged is the student\'s opportunity to connect with a faculty member and peers with common interests in a supportive learning environment.', 'Enrollment limited to students with a term level of Freshman.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Business college.'),
(1121, '3', 'LAUNCH PAD I', 'BA 167', 0, 'Begins a conversation on self-management, offering opportunities for active reflection on critical skill sets necessary for success in today\'s global market. Focused on building a foundation of entrepreneurial knowledge and gaining a competitive edge while becoming aware of your role in managing your own career. BA 167/BA 168 presents an integrated view of both established and entrepreneurial business organizations by studying their common processes and characteristics. The series introduces theory and develops basic skills in the areas of management, finance, accounting, and marketing. Departmental approval required.', 'Enrollment limited to students with a term level of Freshman.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Business college.'),
(1122, '3', 'LAUNCH PAD II', 'BA 168', 0, 'Continues the conversation on self-management, focused on building a foundation of entrepreneurial knowledge and gaining a competitive edge while becoming aware of your role in managing your own career. BA 167/BA 168 presents an integrated view of both established and entrepreneurial business organizations by studying their common processes and characteristics. The series introduces theory and develops basic skills in the areas of management, finance, accounting, and marketing. Departmental approval required.', 'Prerequisite: BA 167.A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 167.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Business college.'),
(1123, '1 to 6', 'SPECIAL STUDIES: SS/ AUSTIN LAB', 'BA 199', 0, 'Graded P/N.', ''),
(1124, '1 to 6', 'INTERNSHIP', 'BA 210', 0, 'Planned and supervised work experience at selected cooperating business firms. Supplementary training, conference, reports, and appraisals. Graded P/N.', 'Enrollment limited to students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Business college.'),
(1125, '4', 'FINANCIAL ACCOUNTING', 'BA 211', 0, 'Accounting information from the perspective of external users, principally investors and creditors. Emphasis on the preparation and interpretation of financial statements, income recognition and determination, and asset valuation.', 'Prerequisites: (MTH 111, 241, 251 or 251H) or minimum score of 24 in \'Math Placement Test\' or minimum score of 060 in \'Math Placement - ALEKS\'.A minimum grade of C- is required in MTH 111, MTH 241, MTH 251 and MTH 251H.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Agricultural Business Manageme (104)Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Management and Marketing (288)Business Engineering (355)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)Agricultural & Food Bus Mgmt (897)'),
(1126, '4', 'MANAGERIAL ACCOUNTING', 'BA 213', 0, 'Accounting information from the perspective of management users with an emphasis on data accumulation for product costing, planning, and performance evaluation and control.', 'Prerequisites: BA 211 or 211H.A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 211 and BA 211H.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Agricultural Business Manageme (104)Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Management and Marketing (288)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)Agricultural & Food Bus Mgmt (897)'),
(1127, '4', 'PRINCIPLES OF MARKETING', 'BA 223', 0, 'Covers concepts and principles used by marketing professionals. Designed explicitly for business majors, it?s an introduction to the relationships between customers, products, and companies in a competitive and dynamically evolving marketplace.', 'Prerequisites: ECON 201 or 201H.A minimum grade of C- is required in ECON 201 and ECON 201H.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Management (196)Apparel Design (400)Merchandising Management (416)Pre-Apparel (453)Pre-Interiors (454)Interior Design (458)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)Design & Innovation Management (912)'),
(1128, '4', 'BUSINESS LAW I', 'BA 230', 0, 'Nature and function of law in our business society. Obligations arising out of agency, contract formation and breach, crimes, torts, warranty, regulation of competition, and international aspects thereof.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)'),
(1129, '4', 'FINANCE', 'BA 240', 0, 'Introduces basic tools of finance and applications of financial theory in use today. These tools include rates of return, the time value of money, those that can be applied to capital budgeting decisions, and the logic and fundamentals of financial statements. It is designed to enhance a student?s approach to financial decision-making and emphasizes quantitative approaches to decision making. This course will also introduce students to equity and debt markets and securities, and serves as a stepping stone to advanced courses in finance.', 'Prerequisites: (BA 211 or 211H) and (ECON 201 or 201H).A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 211, BA 211H, ECON 201 and ECON 201H.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)'),
(1130, '4', 'PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT', 'BA 253', 0, 'Designed to improve the ability of students to describe their accomplishments and sell their ideas in situations like professional networking, company meetings, response to proposals for services, and interviews. It teaches writing skills and workplace integration for new jobs. Particular emphasis is put on verbal communication and preparation for verbal communication. Students will learn to create career plans that require them to research career options and potential employers, and prepare a developmental roadmap that will lead them to success within the chosen profession.', 'Prerequisites: (BA 101, 162 or DHE 160) and (WR 222, 323, 327 or 327H).A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 101, BA 162, DHE 160, WR 222, WR 323, WR 327 and WR 327H.Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
(1131, '4', 'INTRODUCTION TO ENTREPRENEURSHIP', 'BA 260', 0, 'Topics include evaluating entrepreneurial capabilities, creativity, business plan creation, opportunity assessment and feasibility analysis, business implementation, new product introduction, and seeking funds.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Animal Sciences (125)Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)General Horticulture (240)Management and Marketing (288)Apparel Design (400)Merchandising Management (416)Pre-Apparel (453)Pre-Interiors (454)Interior Design (458)Business (523)Business and Entrepreneurship (574)Viticulture and Enology (613)Accountancy (641)Equine (693)Family Business (783)Eco Mgmt Turf, Ldscp, Urb Hort (792)Sustainable Hort Production (798)Marketing (799)Business (803)Entrepreneurship (809)Forest Operations Management (823)Innovation Management (851)Sustainable Tourism Mgmt (874)Nature, Eco, & Adventure Tour (876)Design & Innovation Management (912)'),
(1132, '4', 'BUSINESS PROCESS MANAGEMENT', 'BA 270', 0, 'Introduces and integrates some core concepts from Operations Management (OM) and Business Information System (BIS) disciplines by introducing a process-oriented view of the flows of materials, information, products and services through and across organizational functions. Helps students to: identify information-bearing events and actors, model and analyze business processes, assess and improve process efficiency, recognize probabilistic components of business processes and understand the interactions between human behavior and process design. Hands-on, case-based assignments allow for practicing some principles and concepts addressed in the course.', 'Prerequisites: BA 275 or 275H.A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 275 and BA 275H.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)'),
(1133, '4', 'BUSINESS APPLICATION DEVELOPMENT', 'BA 272', 0, 'Introduction to business programming with C#.NET. Beginning programming skills and concepts, .NET programming environment, object-oriented and event-oriented models, and console applications.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Business Information Systems (183) or Accounting Information Systems (236).'),
(1134, '4', 'FOUNDATIONS OF STATISTICAL INFERENCE', 'BA 275', 0, 'An introductory course on statistical inference with an emphasis on business applications. Coverage includes descriptive statistics, random variables, probability distributions, sampling and sampling distributions, statistical inference for means and proportions using one and two samples, and linear regression analysis.', 'Prerequisites: MTH 111, 241, 251, 251H or minimum score of 046 in \'Math Placement - ALEKS\'.A minimum grade of C- is required in MTH 111, MTH 241, MTH 251 and MTH 251H.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)'),
(1135, '2', 'BUSINESS INSIGHTS', 'BA 280', 0, 'Connect with faculty and peers and explore OSU resources designed to enhance your college experience and success. Engage in professional development activities and cultivate the soft skills employers are looking for in their future employees.', 'Enrollment is limited to Undergraduate level students.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Business college.'),
(1136, '3', 'PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT', 'BA 281', 0, 'Designed to give students an early start on the process of career planning and development. The process involves thoughtful self-assessment, career exploration, planning and follow-through with preliminary employment strategies.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)'),
(1137, '1', 'DRAFTING YOUR CAREER BLUEPRINT', 'BA 282', 0, 'Part of Blueprint ? a 12 course professional development course series to guide the student from college to career. Topics include characteristics of exemplary leadership, analyzing own strengths and talents, and developing a plan for strengthening leadership capacity.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)'),
(1138, '1', 'CREATIVITY, CULTURE, AND THE WORKPLACE', 'BA 283', 0, 'Part of Blueprint ? a 12 course professional development course series to guide the student from college to career. Topics include exploration of students\' unique talents; understanding of how teams as well as organizations can benefit from diverse and inclusive communities.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)Business Analytics (899)'),
(1139, '1', 'PPL DEVELOPMENT III', 'BA 284', 0, 'BA 284, taken during spring term of the second year, course helps students develop lifelong skills that are practical, meaningful, and useful. These skills and the understanding developed through this course strengthens the student\'s ability to adapt career goals to changing market conditions, make good decisions in difficult situations, and set financial goals.', 'Prerequisites: BA 101, 162 or 162H.A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 101, BA 162 and BA 162H.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)Business Analytics (899)'),
(1140, '3', 'INTRODUCTION TO CAREERS IN MARKETING', 'BA 290', 0, 'Explores marketing through the perspectives of current marketing professionals. Introductory language and principles of marketing are introduced and examined through real world examples. Presents various careers within marketing.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to Undergraduate level students.'),
(1141, '1', 'BUSINESS COMMUNICATIONS', 'BA 311', 0, 'Part of Blueprint ? a 12 course professional development course series to guide the student from college to career. Course topics are designed to help the student explore different types of business communications and how to effectively communicate their ideas in a variety of methods.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)'),
(1142, '1', 'THIRD-YEAR PPL DEVELOPMENT I', 'BA 311', 0, 'BA 311 ? BA 313 is a series of three one-credit courses taken during a student?s third year. These courses, along with the respective 1st, 2nd and 4th year one-credit courses, are designed to help students navigate college successfully, and develop lifelong skills that are practical, meaningful, and useful. These courses revolve around personal, professional and leadership development, and the third-year series provides students with skills related to team work and team leadership. BA 311 focuses on diversity and inclusion; BA 312 focuses on teamwork and career preparation; and BA 313 focuses on team leadership.', 'Enrollment limited to students in the College of Business college.'),
(1143, '1', 'FOUNDATIONS OF PERSONAL FINANCE II', 'BA 312', 0, 'Part of Blueprint ? a 12 course professional development course series to guide the student from college to career. The second of a four course series in Blueprint that is dedicated to the foundations of personal finances for life here at OSU.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Apparel Design (400)Merchandising Management (416)Pre-Apparel (453)Pre-Interiors (454)Interior Design (458)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)Business Analytics (899)Design & Innovation Management (912)'),
(1144, '1', 'THIRD YEAR PPL DEVELOPMENT II', 'BA 312', 0, 'BA 311 ? BA 313 is a series of three one-credit courses taken during a student?s third year. These courses, along with the respective 1st, 2nd and 4th year one-credit courses, are designed to help students navigate college successfully, and develop lifelong skills that are practical, meaningful and useful. These courses revolve around personal, professional and leadership development, and the third-year series provides students with skills related to team work and team leadership. BA 311 focuses on diversity and inclusion; BA 312 focuses on teamwork and career preparation; and BA 313 focuses on team leadership.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)Business Analytics (899)'),
(1145, '0 or 1', 'THE ORANGE AND BLACK CASE COMPETITION', 'BA 313', 0, 'Part of Blueprint ? a 12 course professional development course series to guide the student from college to career. Topics include leadership practices; business ethics case competition.', 'Prerequisites: (BA 260 or 260H) and (BA 213 or 213H).A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 260, BA 260H, BA 213 and BA 213H.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Apparel Design (400)Merchandising Management (416)Pre-Apparel (453)Pre-Interiors (454)Interior Design (458)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)Business Analytics (899)Design & Innovation Management (912)'),
(1146, '1', 'THIRD YEAR PPL DEVELOPMENT III', 'BA 313', 0, 'BA 311 ? BA 313 is a series of three one-credit courses taken during a student?s third year. These courses, along with the respective 1st, 2nd and 4th year one-credit courses, are designed to help students navigate college successfully, and develop lifelong skills that are practical, meaningful and useful. These courses revolve around personal, professional and leadership development, and the third-year series provides students with skills related to team work and team leadership. BA 311 focuses on diversity and inclusion; BA 312 focuses on teamwork and career preparation; and BA 313 focuses on team leadership.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)Business Analytics (899)'),
(1147, '4', 'SUSTAINABLE BUSINESS OPERATIONS', 'BA 314', 0, 'Operations are the processes by which an organization transforms inputs (e.g., labor, material, and knowledge) into outputs (products and services). Operations managers are responsible for designing, running and improving the processes and systems to efficiently accomplish this for production or service businesses. This course focuses on the concepts and tools employed by operations managers to provide their organization a competitive advantage. Topics include statistical tools and quantitative methods (descriptive statistics, probabilities, sampling, interval estimation and hypothesis testing) and operations management concepts (strategies, forecasting, process design, capacity utilization, quality systems, supply chain management, inventory management, resource planning, sustainability and lean systems.)', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Pre-MBA (205)Business Administration (2050)Business and Entrepreneurship (574)Business (803)Forest Operations Management (823)'),
(1148, '4', 'ACCOUNTING FOR DECISION MAKING', 'BA 315', 0, 'Looks at how the accounting model reflects business transactions and events. Students are introduced to both financial and managerial accounting and the creation, interpretation, and analysis of financial statements. In addition, students obtain an understanding of the determination, organization, and management of costs and revenues including management decisions based upon this information.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Animal Sciences (125)Pre-MBA (205)Business Administration (2050)General Horticulture (240)Health Management and Policy (242)Agricultural Sciences (259)Nutrition and Foodservice Sys (261)Science and Engineering (289)Construction Engineering Mgt (338)Pre-Construction Engr Mgt (368)Apparel Design (400)Merchandising Management (416)Pre-Apparel (453)Pre-Interiors (454)Interior Design (458)Business (523)Business and Entrepreneurship (574)Viticulture and Enology (613)Family & Consumer Sci Teaching (65)Equine (693)Animal Production (708)Family Business (783)Eco Mgmt Turf, Ldscp, Urb Hort (792)Advanced Wood Manufacturing (793)Sustainable Hort Production (798)Business (803)Entrepreneurship (809)Finance (813)Forest Operations Management (823)Innovation Management (851)Managerial Economics (886)Design & Innovation Management (912)'),
(1149, '4', 'LEGAL ENVIRONMENT OF BUSINESS', 'BA 330', 0, 'Nature and function of law in our business society. Obligations arising out of agency, contract formation and breach, crimes, torts, warranty, regulation of competition, and international aspects thereof.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Agricultural Business Manageme (104)Animal Sciences (125)Pre-MBA (205)Business Administration (2050)Interior Design (224)Agricultural Sciences (259)Nutrition and Foodservice Sys (261)Management and Marketing (288)Science and Engineering (289)Construction Engineering Mgt (338)Business Engineering (355)Pre-Construction Engr Mgt (368)Merchandising Management (416)Business and Entrepreneurship (574)Equine (693)Animal Production (708)Business (803)Forest Operations Management (823)Agricultural & Food Bus Mgmt (897)'),
(1150, '4', 'INTERNATIONAL BUSINESS', 'BA 347', 0, 'Integrated view of international business including current patterns of international business, socioeconomic and geopolitical systems within countries as they affect the conduct of business, major theories explaining international business transactions, financial forms and institutions that facilitate international transactions, and the interface between nation states and the firms conducting foreign business activities.', 'Prerequisites: (ECON 202 or 202H) and (BA 230, 230H or 330).A minimum grade of C- is required in ECON 202, ECON 202H, BA 230, BA 230H and BA 330.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Agricultural Business Manageme (104)Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)International Business (190)Management (196)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)Agricultural & Food Bus Mgmt (897)Asian Studies (938)'),
(1151, '1', 'INTERNATIONAL EXCHANGE ORIENTATION', 'BA 348', 0, 'Consists of large-group sessions as well as small-group break-out sessions for each country individually. It is vital to attend all sessions as valuable information pertaining to your study abroad opportunity will be presented. Graded P/N.', ''),
(1152, '1', 'IMPACT OF CULTURE ON BUSINESS', 'BA 349', 0, 'A requirement of all students participating in a College of Business-approved international exchange program and for completing the College of Business International Business option. The major emphasis is for students to reflect on their experience while studying, living and traveling in a foreign culture and for them to determine how the foreign culture impacts how they would conduct business in that country. Graded P/N.', 'Prerequisite: BA 348*.* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 348.Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
(1153, '4', 'MANAGING ORGANIZATIONS', 'BA 351', 0, 'A systems perspective to understanding the management functions of planning, organizing, leading and controlling. Ethical and diversity issues are addressed as they are relevant in entrepreneurial and established ventures.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Agricultural Business Manageme (104)Interior Design (224)Health Management and Policy (242)Nutrition and Foodservice Sys (261)Management and Marketing (288)Energy Systems Engineering (293)Construction Engineering Mgt (338)Dietetics (419)Business (523)Business and Entrepreneurship (574)Family & Consumer Sci Teaching (65)Family Business (783)Food Manufacturing (797)Business (803)Forest Operations Management (823)Innovation Management (851)Sustainability (870)Sustainability (871)Nature, Eco, & Adventure Tour (876)Managerial Economics (886)Agricultural & Food Bus Mgmt (897)'),
(1154, '4', 'MANAGING INDIVIDUAL AND TEAM PERFORMANCE', 'BA 352', 0, 'Diagnose individual and small-group behavior and develop skill in improving individual and small-group performance in entrepreneurial and established ventures. Emphasis on professional skill development and the practical application of theory and research. Concepts of ethics, diversity and cross-cultural relations are integrated throughout the course.', 'Prerequisites: (COMM 111, 111H, 114, 114H, 218 or 218H) and (WR 222, 323, 327, 327H or HC 199).A minimum grade of C- is required in COMM 111, COMM 111H, COMM 114, COMM 114H, COMM 218, COMM 218H, WR 222, WR 323, WR 327, WR 327H and HC 199.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.'),
(1155, '4', '^MANAGING ETHICS AND CORPORATE SOCIAL RESPONSIBILITY', 'BA 354', 0, 'Introduces contemporary issues that business professionals face making ethical and socially responsible decisions in an increasingly fast-paced, transparent, and global environment. (Writing Intensive Course)', 'Prerequisites: (COMM 111, 111H, 114, 114H, 218 or 218H) and (WR 222, 323, 327, 327H or HC 199).A minimum grade of C- is required in COMM 111, COMM 111H, COMM 114, COMM 114H, COMM 218, COMM 218H, WR 222, WR 323, WR 327, WR 327H and HC 199.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Management (196)Apparel Design (400)Merchandising Management (416)Pre-Apparel (453)Pre-Interiors (454)Interior Design (458)Accountancy (641)Marketing (799)Innovation Management (851)Design & Innovation Management (912)'),
(1156, '4', 'OPERATIONS MANAGEMENT', 'BA 357', 0, 'Decision making in managing the production of goods and services: product planning, process planning, facility planning, control of quantity, cost and quality. Special emphasis on exponential forecasting, inventory management, work methods, project management, productivity improvement, and international comparisons.', 'Prerequisites: BA 275, 275H or 276.A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 275, BA 275H and BA 276.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Pre-MBA (205)Business Administration (2050)Management and Marketing (288)Energy Systems Engineering (293)Accountancy (641)Food Manufacturing (797)Marketing (799)'),
(1157, '4', 'INTRODUCTION TO FINANCIAL MANAGEMENT', 'BA 360', 0, 'Explore the issues facing a financial manager in new business ventures, small businesses, and corporations. Focus on the role of the financial manager in business settings, explores the functions of a financial manager in financial analysis, forecasting, planning, and control; asset and liability management; capital budgeting; and raising funds for new business ventures, small businesses, and corporations.', 'Prerequisites: ((BA 211 or 211H) or (BA 215 or 215H) or BA 315) and ((ECON 201 or 201H) or (AEC 250 or 250H) or AEC 251).A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 211, BA 211H, BA 215, BA 215H, BA 315, ECON 201, ECON 201H, AEC 250, AEC 250H and AEC 251.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Agricultural Business Manageme (104)Business Administration (181)Finance (182)Business Information Systems (183)Undecided Business Administrat (185)Management (196)Pre-MBA (205)Business Administration (2050)Health Management and Policy (242)Nutrition and Foodservice Sys (261)Management and Marketing (288)Business (523)Business and Entrepreneurship (574)Accountancy (641)Family Business (783)Marketing (799)Business (803)Finance (813)Managerial Economics (886)Agricultural & Food Bus Mgmt (897)'),
(1158, '4', 'SOCIAL ENTREPRENEURSHIP AND SOCIAL INITIATIVES', 'BA 362', 0, 'The core concepts of entrepreneurship, using entrepreneurship to craft innovative responses to social problems. Entrepreneurial skills are as valuable in the social sector as they are in business. Includes both profit and non-profit firms that have programs designed to create social value.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.'),
(1159, '4', 'TECHNOLOGY AND INNOVATION MANAGEMENT', 'BA 363', 0, 'Introduces students to the fundamentals of managing innovation and technology toward the production of intellectual assets; how innovations are created, evaluated and leveraged within business strategy; and how innovation is managed within various business environments.', 'Prerequisites: BA 260 or 260H.A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 260 and BA 260H.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.'),
(1160, '4', 'FAMILY BUSINESS MANAGEMENT', 'BA 365', 0, 'Focuses on the opportunities and the problems characteristic of family businesses: entrepreneurship, management succession, transfer of ownership, mixing family and business roles, family conflicts, personnel issues, non-family employees, and outside advisors.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.'),
(1161, '3', 'LAUNCH ACADEMY', 'BA 367', 0, 'The Oregon State Launch Academy is an incubator for student entrepreneurs who want to be immersed in an innovative, high-energy environment that promotes the creation, evolution and implementation of business ideas. Launch Academy students earn academic credit for working on their businesses and have access to seed funding, prototyping equipment, co-working space, mentoring and training to help them advance their ideas. Launch Academy students learn about developing new products or services, marketing their ideas, building teams and securing funding, among other critical elements of entrepreneurial success.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.');
