(1521, '4', 'FINITE ELEMENT ANALYSIS', 'CE 532', 2, 'Applications of the finite element method to structural analysis, fluid flow and elasticity problems. Use and development of large finite element computer programs.', 'Prerequisites: (CE 585 or ME 520).A minimum grade of C is required in CE 585 and ME 520.'),
(1522, '3', 'STRUCTURAL STABILITY', 'CE 533', 2, 'Stability theory and applications, with emphasis on design of steel structures.', ''),
(1523, '4', 'MATRIX METHODS OF STRUCTURAL ANALYSIS', 'CE 536', 2, 'Development of matrix methods for linear structural analysis. Force and displacement methods of analysis. Virtual work principles. Use of computer programs to analyze structures. Introduction to the finite-element method.', 'Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(1524, '4', 'NONLINEAR STRUCTURAL ANALYSIS', 'CE 537', 2, 'Material and geometric nonlinear analysis of frame and truss structures. Solution strategies for nonlinear structural analysis. Nonlinear constitutive models of steel and reinforced concrete members. Development and use of computer programs for nonlinear analysis.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(1525, '4', 'WATER RESOURCES ENGINEERING I: PRINCIPLES OF FLUID MECHANICS', 'CE 547', 2, 'Fluid mechanics for water resources engineers, classifications of fluid flows; fluid statics and dynamics, incompressible viscous flows; dimensional analysis; applications to fluid machinery, flow through porous media, fluid motion in rivers, lakes, oceans.', ''),
(1526, '3', 'TRANSPORTATION SAFETY ANALYSIS', 'CE 556', 2, 'Provides students with a general knowledge of major transportation safety issues and a general background in the application of various statistical and econometric safety analysis techniques. In addition, this course presents a number of model-estimation methods used in transportation safety data analysis, and other subject areas that deal with safety analysis.', ''),
(1527, '3', 'ST IN GEOMATICS ENGINEERING: ST/ ADVANCED GIS', 'CE 560', 2, 'Selected topics on contemporary problems in geomatics engineering; application of ongoing research from resident and visiting faculty.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(1528, '3', 'ST IN GEOMATICS ENGINEERING: ST/ HYDROGRAPHIC SURVEYING', 'CE 560', 2, 'Selected topics on contemporary problems in geomatics engineering; application of ongoing research from resident and visiting faculty.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(1529, '3', 'PHOTOGRAMMETRY', 'CE 561', 2, 'Geometry of terrestrial and vertical photographs, flightline planning, stereoscopy and parallax, stereoscopic plotting instruments, analytical photogrammetry, orthophotography, introduction to photo interpretation, and aerial cameras.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(1530, '4', 'DIGITAL TERRAIN MODELING', 'CE 562', 2, 'Fundamentals of LIDAR and creating digital terrain models. Computational geometry, Delaunay triangulations, spline interpolations, statistical gridding methods, ground filtering, data optimizations, and advanced topics in 3D modeling.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(1531, '4', 'CONTROL SURVEYING', 'CE 563', 2, 'Global Positioning Systems (GPS) theory, networks, and fieldwork; control specifications, methods and problems in obtaining large area measurements; precise leveling; network adjustments using least square techniques; field instrument adjustments.', ''),
(1532, '3', 'OREGON LAND SURVEY LAW', 'CE 565', 2, 'Introduction to U.S. public land survey; Oregon state statutes, common law decisions, and administrative rules dealing with boundary law; case studies; unwritten land transfers; original and resurvey platting laws; guarantees of title; deed descriptions.', ''),
(1533, '4', '3D LASER SCANNING AND IMAGING', 'CE 566', 2, 'Fundamentals of lidar acquisition, registration, processing, modeling, analysis, and verification. Use of sensor platforms for 3D acquisition. Effective data management procedures. Introduction to other imaging techniques including structure from motion and structured light. Lec/lab.', ''),
(1534, '3', 'PROPERTY SURVEYS', 'CE 569', 2, 'U.S. public land survey: restoration of corners, subdivision of sections; topographic mapping; subdivision and partition plats, resurvey plats, subdivision design; introduction to LIS/GIS; field astronomy.', ''),
(1535, '3', 'GEOTECHNICAL SPECIAL TOPICS: ST/MATHEMATICAL METHODS IN ENG', 'CE 570', 2, 'Development and management of actual projects through the examination of case histories; evaluation of geotechnical data; development of design recommendations and preparation of project reports.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate or Professional level students.'),
(1536, '4', 'ADVANCED FOUNDATION ENGINEERING', 'CE 571', 2, 'Presents the planning, analysis, and design of shallow and deep foundations from the geotechnical engineering perspective. Topics supporting course objectives include planning and execution of subsurface investigations, interpretation of in-situ tests, analysis and design of deep and shallow foundations, including geotechnical capacity, and immediate settlement. Assessment of deep foundation installation, axial and lateral loading tests, and group effects is presented. Evaluation of foundation performance is conducted under deterministic and probabilistic frameworks.', ''),
(1537, '4', 'ADVANCED GEOTECHNICAL LABORATORY', 'CE 572', 2, 'Examination of soil composition and engineering properties of soils including volume change, pore pressure generation, strength, and deformation behavior of soils in the laboratory. Advanced static and cyclic shear strength testing of soils will also be discussed. Lec/lab.', ''),
(1538, '3', 'STATIC AND DYNAMIC SOIL BEHAVIOR', 'CE 577', 2, 'An advanced coverage of volume change and strength behavior of soil. Specific course topics include effective stress, one-dimensional compression of soil, rate of soil consolidation, Mohr circle analysis, shear strength of sands, clays, and silts, and dynamic soil properties, strength, and testing.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(1539, '4', 'GEOTECHNICAL EARTHQUAKE ENGINEERING', 'CE 578', 2, 'Major course topics include engineering seismology, strong ground motion, seismic hazard analysis, soil dynamics, seismic site response, earthquake motion selection, liquefaction, and seismic slope stability. Attention will be given to earthquakes created by the Cascadia Subduction Zone. Lec/lab.', ''),
(1540, '3', 'ST/STRUCTURAL DESIGN: ST/ADV STEEL DESIGN', 'CE 580', 2, 'A critical examination in depth of topics selected by the instructor from among topics not covered in other structural design courses.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(1541, '3', 'ST/STRUCTURAL DESIGN: ST/ADVANCED RC DESIGN', 'CE 580', 2, 'A critical examination in depth of topics selected by the instructor from among topics not covered in other structural design courses.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(1542, '3', 'ST/STRUCTURAL DESIGN: ST/STRUCTURAL FIRE ENGINEERING', 'CE 580', 2, 'A critical examination in depth of topics selected by the instructor from among topics not covered in other structural design courses.', ''),
(1543, '4', 'REINFORCED CONCRETE I', 'CE 581', 2, 'Basic principles of reinforced concrete design; strength, stability, and serviceability criteria; design of reinforced concrete members for flexure and shear. Detailing, development length and splices.', 'Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering or College of Forestry colleges.'),
(1544, '3', 'MASONRY DESIGN', 'CE 582', 2, 'A critical examination in depth of masonry design topics.', ''),
(1545, '3', 'BRIDGE DESIGN', 'CE 583', 2, 'AASHTO specifications for bridge design; load models; design for moving loads; design and analysis of bridge decks and simple and continuous bridge spans.', ''),
(1546, '4', 'WOOD DESIGN', 'CE 584', 2, 'Study of basic wood properties and design considerations. Design and behavior of wood connectors, beams, columns and beam columns. Introduction to plywood and glued laminated members. Analysis and design of structural diaphragms and shear walls. Lec/lab. CROSSLISTED as CE 584/WSE 558.', ''),
(1547, '3', 'PRESTRESSED CONCRETE', 'CE 586', 2, 'Prestressed concrete analysis and design, systems of prestressing, materials, economics.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(1548, '4', 'SEISMIC DESIGN', 'CE 589', 2, 'Design of structures to resist the effects of earthquakes. Introduction to structural dynamics, dynamic analysis, seismic design philosophy, code requirements, and detailing for steel and reinforced concrete.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(1549, '3', 'SELECTED TOPICS IN TRANSPORTATION ENGINEERING', 'CE 590', 2, 'Selected topics on contemporary problems in transportation engineering; application of ongoing research from resident and visiting faculty.', 'Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(1550, '3', 'ST/TRANSPORTATION ENGR: ST/ AGENT BASED MODELING', 'CE 590', 2, 'Selected topics on contemporary problems in transportation engineering; application of ongoing research from resident and visiting faculty.', ''),
(1551, '3', 'TRANSPORTATION SYSTEMS ANALYSIS, PLANNING, AND POLICY', 'CE 591', 2, 'The systems approach and its applications to transportation engineering and planning. The making of transportation plans and policies. Development of transportation models. Transportation system performance. Decision analysis. Evaluation of transportation projects. Environmental and social impacts of transportation.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(1552, '3', 'PAVEMENT STRUCTURES', 'CE 592', 2, 'Design and rehabilitation of pavement structures for streets, highways, and airports.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(1553, '4', 'TRANSPORT FACILITY DESIGN', 'CE 594', 2, 'Location and design of highways, and other surface transportation terminals; design for safety, energy efficiency, and environmental quality. Offered alternate years. Lec/rec.', ''),
(1554, '3', 'TRAFFIC OPERATIONS AND DESIGN', 'CE 595', 2, 'Traffic operations and engineering; human and vehicular characteristics; traffic stream characteristics; highway capacity analysis; intersection operation, control and design.', ''),
(1555, '3', 'PAVEMENT EVALUATION AND MANAGEMENT', 'CE 596', 2, 'Advanced topics in pavement evaluation techniques and pavement management procedures.', ''),
(1556, '3', 'AIRPORT PLANNING AND DESIGN', 'CE 598', 2, 'Characteristics and nature of the air transport system. Airport financing, air traffic control. Analysis and design of airports and the airport planning processes. Airport appurtenances. Airport pavement design, environmental facilities and drainage. Offered alternate years.', ''),
