(1680, '4', 'OBTAINING CONSTRUCTION CONTRACTS', 'CEM 431', 0, 'Preparing and effectively presenting detailed and complete proposals for the execution of construction projects.', 'Prerequisite: CEM 341.A minimum grade of C is required in CEM 341.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Construction Engineering Mgt (338).'),
(1681, '3', 'CONSTRUCTION PROJECT PLANNING', 'CEM 432', 0, 'Planning and preparing cost estimates, schedules, site logistics plans for executing construction projects; presenting written and oral construction proposals.', 'Prerequisite: CEM 341.A minimum grade of C is required in CEM 341.'),
(1682, '4', 'HEAVY CIVIL CONSTRUCTION MANAGEMENT', 'CEM 441', 0, 'Heavy civil construction management methods. Construction equipment types, capabilities, costs, productivity, and the selection and planning of equipment needed for a project. Soil characteristics, quantity analysis, and movement on construction sites.', 'Prerequisites: FE 315 or CE 372.A minimum grade of C is required in FE 315 and CE 372.Enrollment is limited to students with a major in Construction Engineering Mgt (338).'),
(1683, '4', 'BUILDING CONSTRUCTION MANAGEMENT', 'CEM 442', 0, 'Building construction management and methods.', 'Prerequisites: CCE 207 or CEM 407.A minimum grade of C is required in CCE 207 and CEM 407.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Construction Engineering Mgt (338), Construction Engineering Mgt (3380) or Architectural Engineering (826).Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(1684, '4', '^PROJECT MANAGEMENT FOR CONSTRUCTION', 'CEM 443', 0, 'Project management concepts for construction; concepts, roles and responsibilities, labor relations and supervision, administrative systems, documentation, quality management, and process improvement. (Writing Intensive Course)', 'Prerequisites: CEM 341 and 343.A minimum grade of C is required in CEM 341 and CEM 343.Enrollment is limited to students with a major in Construction Engineering Mgt (338).'),
(1685, '4', 'ELECTRICAL FACILITIES', 'CEM 471', 0, 'Principles and applications of electrical components of constructed facilities; basic electrical circuit theory, power, motors, controls, codes, and building distribution systems. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisites: CCE 207 or CEM 407.A minimum grade of C is required in CCE 207 and CEM 407.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Construction Engineering Mgt (338) or Architectural Engineering (826).'),
(1686, '3', 'MECHANICAL FACILITIES', 'CEM 472', 0, 'Principles and applications of mechanical components of constructed facilities; heating, ventilating, air conditioning, plumbing, fire protection, and other mechanical construction.', 'Prerequisites: CCE 207 or CEM 407.A minimum grade of C is required in CCE 207 and CEM 407.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Construction Engineering Mgt (338).'),
(1687, '4', 'HEAVY CIVIL CONSTRUCTION MANAGEMENT', 'CEM 541', 2, 'Heavy civil construction management methods. Construction equipment types, capabilities, costs, productivity, and the selection and planning of equipment needed for a project. Soil characteristics, quantity analysis, and movement on construction sites.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(1688, '4', 'CONTEMPORARY TOPICS IN CEM: CONTEMPORARY TOPICS/ SIMU', 'CEM 550', 2, 'Contemporary topics of emerging technologies and processes, construction engineering and management, how industry environmental change causes development of new technologies, and the applications of the technologies in the field.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(1689, '4', 'PROJECT CONTROLS', 'CEM 551', 2, 'Advanced methods of project controls including advanced technologies and methodologies for quality, time, and cost management; project management organization models, and intra-organizational relationships.', ''),
(1690, '3', 'PERSONAL GROWTH AND WELLNESS IN THE MODERN WORLD', 'COUN 421', 0, 'Explores social and emotional adjustment, growth, and wellness within current social contexts.  Examines challenges to wellness and the role of normal development, self-help, and the helping professions in the growth process.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
(1691, '3', 'INTRODUCTION TO PROFESSIONAL COUNSELING', 'COUN 441', 0, 'Provides students with an overview of the counseling profession that includes the history and philosophical foundations of the profession and roles and functions of professional counselors. The course content will critically engage the privilege and responsibility of the counseling profession in a multicultural society.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
(1692, '2', 'SPECIAL TOPICS: Independent Research', 'COUN 499', 0, '', 'Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
(1693, '3', 'SPECIAL TOPICS: ST/ ADDICTIONS & MENTAL HEALTH', 'COUN 499', 0, '', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
(1694, '3', 'SPECIAL TOPICS: ST/ADDICTIONS & MENTAL HEALTH', 'COUN 499', 0, '', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
