(1810, '4', 'PERFORMANCE APPAREL INNOVATION I', 'DSGN 327', 0, 'Develop innovative performance apparel from technical specifications or prototypes. Analysis of apparel construction related to equipment, cost, quality, end use and customer needs. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 226.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 226.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Apparel Design (400) or Apparel Design (780).'),
(1811, '3', 'DIGITAL DESIGN FOR APPAREL', 'DSGN 328', 0, 'Computer-aided flat pattern, grading and marker techniques using industry relevant pattern development software.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 327.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 327.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Apparel Design (400) or Apparel Design (780).'),
(1812, '3', 'SPORTSWEAR INDUSTRY COLLABORATION', 'DSGN 329', 0, 'Industry lead team project. Creation of briefs, sketch, pattern, design textile prints, construct prototypes based on identified consumer and company.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 327.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 327.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Apparel Design (400).'),
(1813, '4', '^FASHION FORECASTING AND MARKET ANALYSIS', 'DSGN 330', 0, 'Forecasting and market analysis processes applied to fashion goods. (Writing Intensive Course)', 'Prerequisites: WR 222, 323 or 327.A minimum grade of C- is required in WR 222, WR 323 and WR 327.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Apparel Design (400), Merchandising Management (416), Apparel Design (780) or Merchandising Management (782).'),
(1814, '4', 'HISTORY OF CONTEMPORARY FASHION', 'DSGN 333', 0, 'Historic analysis of fashion change in men?s and women?s apparel from 1890 to the present. The influence of social and cultural factors upon Euro-American fashion.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Apparel Design (400), Merchandising Management (416) or Apparel Design (780).'),
(1815, '4', 'DESIGN THINKING AND PROCESS INNOVATION', 'DSGN 341', 0, 'Application of a qualitative, multi-method approach to gain insight into how the consumer experience can be improved within a given context. Application of design thinking principles to identify and develop solutions to improve consumer experience within a given context.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Apparel Design (400)Merchandising Management (416)Pre-Apparel (453)Pre-Interiors (454)Interior Design (458)Design & Innovation Management (912)'),
(1816, '4', 'INTRODUCTION TO DESIGN MANAGEMENT', 'DSGN 342', 0, 'Introduces the foundations and concepts of design strategy and creative development.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 341.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 341.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Design & Innovation Management (912).'),
(1817, '4', 'IDEA VISUALIZATION', 'DSGN 343', 0, 'Focuses on the design process through visual communication of ideation and sketching.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 342.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 342.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Design & Innovation Management (912).'),
(1818, '3', 'SPECIFICATION AND EVALUATION OF PERFORMANCE MATERIALS', 'DSGN 356', 0, 'Specification of materials for athletic and outdoor apparel to enhance human comfort, safety, and performance.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 255.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 255.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Apparel Design (400), Merchandising Management (416) or Design & Innovation Management (912).'),
(1819, '1', 'EVALUATION OF PERFORMANCE MATERIALS LABORATORY', 'DSGN 357', 0, 'Evaluation of materials for athletic and outdoor apparel to enhance human comfort, safety, and performance.', 'Prerequisites: DSGN 255 and 327.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 255 and DSGN 327.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Apparel Design (400).'),
(1820, '4', 'MERCHANDISE PLANNING AND CONTROL', 'DSGN 372', 0, 'Quantitative analysis of inventory planning, pricing, and control for the profitable management of soft goods; analysis of management problems using quantitative data and merchandising principles.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 276.A minimum grade of C is required in DSGN 276.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Merchandising Management (416) or Merchandising Management (782).'),
(1821, '4', 'RETAIL AND MERCHANDISING', 'DSGN 377', 0, 'Evaluation of performance within the merchandising functions of an organization. Development of merchandising plans based on quantitative and qualitative analysis, as well merchandising principles.', 'Prerequisites: DSGN 372 or 472.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 372 and DSGN 472.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Merchandising Management (416) or Merchandising Management (782).'),
(1822, '3', 'BUILDING CONSTRUCTION AND MATERIALS', 'DSGN 383', 0, 'An introduction to the manufacture, characteristics, sustainability, and use of construction materials in commercial and residential construction.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Interior Design (224) or Interior Design (458).'),
(1823, '4', 'STUDIO III: ADVANCED DESIGN COMMUNICATION', 'DSGN 387', 0, 'Development of presentation and Building Information Modeling (BIM) skills through various computer programs including Adobe Illustrator, Adobe PhotoShop, Sketchup, and Revit Architecture. In-class exercises and take-home assignments.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 287.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 287.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Interior Design (224) or Interior Design (458).'),
(1824, '4', 'STUDIO IV: HOSPITALITY DESIGN', 'DSGN 388', 0, 'Study and design of hospitality spaces in compliance with building codes and industry standards, with emphasis on sustainability, safety, and cultural context.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 387.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 387.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Interior Design (458).'),
(1825, '0 or 4', 'STUDIO V: LIGHTING DESIGN', 'DSGN 394', 0, 'Lighting design and documentation for residential and small commercial projects. The commercial projects include space planning and lighting design for workspace and retail environments. Lec/Studio.', 'Prerequisites: DSGN 388 or DHE 388.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 388 and DHE 388.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.'),
(1826, '1 to 16', 'PROJECTS: PROJECTS / COLLECTION', 'DSGN 406', 0, '', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a major in Apparel Design (400), Merchandising Management (416), Interior Design (458) or Design & Innovation Management (912).'),
(1827, '1 to 16', 'PROJECTS: PROJECTS/ COLLECTION', 'DSGN 406', 0, '', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Apparel Design (400), Merchandising Management (416), Interior Design (458) or Design & Innovation Management (912).'),
(1828, '1 to 6', 'DESIGN INTERNSHIP', 'DSGN 410', 0, 'Planned and supervised work experience at selected cooperating business firms. Supplementary training, conference, reports, and appraisals. Graded P/N.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Apparel Design (400), Merchandising Management (416), Interior Design (458) or Design & Innovation Management (912).'),
(1829, '1', 'FOURTH YEAR PERSONAL, PROFESSIONAL, & LEADERSHIP DEVELOPMENT', 'DSGN 411', 0, 'DSGN 411 ? DSGN 413 is a series of three one-credit courses taken during your fourth year. These courses along with the respective 2nd and 3rd year one-credit courses are designed to help you successfully navigate college and develop lifelong skills that are practical, meaningful and useful. These courses revolve around personal, professional and leadership development, and the fourth year series continue to provide students with career-related skills as they seek out full-time employment. DSGN 411 focuses on career placement skills; DSGN 412 focuses on self-leadership; and DSGN 413 focuses on work-life balance, financial literacy, and networking.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.'),
(1830, '4', 'PERFORMANCE APPAREL INNOVATION II', 'DSGN 427', 0, 'Develop innovative performance apparel from technical specifications or prototypes. Analysis of apparel construction related to equipment, cost, quality, end use and customer needs. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 327.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 327.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Apparel Design (400) or Apparel Design (780).'),
(1831, '4', 'TECHNICAL SPORTSWEAR SIZING AND FIT', 'DSGN 428', 0, 'Development of sizing and grading systems used in sportswear and evaluation of garment fit by use of virtual and physical prototypes.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 327.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 327.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Apparel Design (400) or Apparel Design (780).'),
(1832, '4', 'FUNCTIONAL DESIGN AND PRODUCT DEVELOPMENT', 'DSGN 429', 0, 'Design processes and research methods used to create functional designs. Students will identify design problems and develop design brief and functional product line for identified target company. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 428.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 428.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Apparel Design (400) or Apparel Design (780).'),
(1833, '4', 'DESIGN RESEARCH', 'DSGN 440', 0, 'Surveys design principles, methods and applications in business outcomes. Application of design research is investigated and analyzed in group projects.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 343.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 343.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Design Management (781).'),
(1834, '4', 'SERVICE DESIGN INNOVATION', 'DSGN 441', 0, 'Focuses on the impact that service design has on business enterprises. Creative ideation, critical analysis, and innovative thinking are integrated as foundations for service design outcomes.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 440.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 440.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Design & Innovation Management (912).'),
(1835, '4', 'MATERIALITY AND MAKING FIELD PROJECT', 'DSGN 442', 0, 'Focuses on material properties and specifications. Students work in the makerspace to design product outcomes.', 'Prerequisites: DHE 440 or DSGN 440.A minimum grade of C- is required in DHE 440 and DSGN 440.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Design & Innovation Management (912).'),
(1836, '3', 'CONTEMPORARY HISTORY OF INTERIORS AND HOUSING', 'DSGN 464', 0, 'History of interior design from the mid-19th century to the present.', 'Prerequisites: ART 204, 205 or 206.A minimum grade of C- is required in ART 204, ART 205 and ART 206.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Interior Design (224) or Interior Design (458).'),
(1837, '4', 'RETAIL PRESENTATION STRATEGIES', 'DSGN 471', 0, 'Provides an overview of, and examines competitive presentation strategies within, retail environments and channels (e.g., in-store, catalog, online, mobile) by integrating the principles and elements of design with sensory marketing.', 'Prerequisites: DSGN 377 and (BA 390, 390H, 223, 223H or MRKT 390).A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 377, BA 390, BA 390H, BA 223, BA 223H and MRKT 390.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Merchandising Management (416) or Merchandising Management (782).'),
(1838, '4', '*GLOBAL SOURCING OF TEXTILES, APPAREL, AND FOOTWEAR', 'DSGN 475', 0, 'Trade theory and the effects of trade policy, cultural values, and economics on the global production, distribution, and consumption of textiles, apparel, and footwear. (Bacc Core Course)', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.'),
(1839, '4', 'STUDIO VI: HEALTHCARE DESIGN', 'DSGN 488', 0, 'Interior design project development with emphasis on healthcare design, contract documents, and building codes.', 'Prerequisites: DSGN 394 or DHE 394.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 394 and DHE 394.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Interior Design (224) or Interior Design (458).'),
(1840, '4', 'STUDIO VII: SENIOR THESIS II', 'DSGN 495', 0, 'Individual design project development of programming document and construction drawings.', 'Prerequisite: DSGN 488.A minimum grade of C- is required in DSGN 488.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Interior Design (224) or Interior Design (458).'),
(1841, '4', '*INTRODUCTION TO MICROECONOMICS', 'ECON 201', 0, 'An introduction to microeconomic principles including the study of price theory, economic scarcity, consumer behavior, production costs, the theory of the firm, market structure, and income distribution. Other selected topics may include market failure, international economics, and public finance. (SS) (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(1842, '4', '*INTRODUCTION TO MACROECONOMICS', 'ECON 202', 0, 'An introduction to macroeconomic principles including study of the theories of output determination, consumption, investment, inflation, unemployment, and fiscal and monetary policy. Other selected topics may include the study of the international balance of payments, growth and development, and urban and regional problems. (SS) (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(1843, '4', 'INTERMEDIATE MICROECONOMIC THEORY', 'ECON 311', 0, 'An examination of demand theory, production and cost theory, game theory, behavioral economics, competitive and imperfectly competitive markets, and general equilibrium and welfare economics. ECON 311 and ECON 411 cannot both be taken for credit toward the economics major.', 'Prerequisites: ECON 201 or 201H.A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 201 and ECON 201H.'),
(1844, '4', 'INTERMEDIATE MACROECONOMIC THEORY', 'ECON 315', 0, 'An examination of macroeconomic aggregates, income determination, aggregate demand and supply. The basic macroeconomic models will be discussed such as Keynesian, Classical, Monetarist, and Neo-Classical. ECON 315 and ECON 415 cannot both be taken for credit toward the Economics major.', 'Prerequisites: (ECON 201 or 201H) and (ECON 202 or 202H).A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 201, ECON 201H, ECON 202 and ECON 202H.'),
(1845, '4', 'INTRODUCTION TO MATHEMATICAL ECONOMICS', 'ECON 329', 0, 'Mathematical methods of economic analysis. Theory of economic structure and optimization developed through calculus and linear algebra, dynamic systems analyzed through integral calculus and difference and differential equations. The mathematical tools are developed in conjunction with their application to economic problems. Some acquaintance with calculus recommended.', 'Prerequisites: (ECON 201 or 201H) and (ECON 202 or 202H) and (MTH 241, 251 or 251H).A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 201, ECON 201H, ECON 202, ECON 202H, MTH 241, MTH 251 and MTH 251H.'),
(1846, '4', 'MONEY AND BANKING', 'ECON 330', 0, 'Nature and functions of money; functions and operations of depository institutions; the money market; central banking and monetary policy. (SS)', 'Prerequisites: (ECON 201 or 201H) and (ECON 202 or 202H).A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 201, ECON 201H, ECON 202 and ECON 202H.'),
(1847, '4', 'INTERNATIONAL ECONOMICS', 'ECON 340', 0, 'An overview of international economics with an emphasis on current events and applications, including classical and modern trade theory and the study of trade and exchange-rate policies. (SS) (See Schedule Comment regarding Bacc Core status.)', 'Prerequisites: (ECON 201 or 201H) and (ECON 202 or 202H).A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 201, ECON 201H, ECON 202 and ECON 202H.Enrollment limited to students in the Dist. Degree Corvallis Student or Oregon State - Cascades campuses.'),
(1848, '4', 'FINANCIAL ECONOMICS', 'ECON 350', 0, 'Discusses how various securities meet the needs of different economic agents and the efficiency of financial markets in meeting those needs. Topics include interest rates, valuation, investment risk, trading and market structure, arbitrage, market efficiency, debt markets, equity markets, and financial derivatives.', 'Prerequisites: ECON 201 and 202.A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 201 and ECON 202.'),
(1849, '3', '*ENVIRONMENTAL ECONOMICS AND POLICY', 'ECON 352', 0, 'Provides an overview of the interrelationships between economic activity, the environment, and public policy. Through case studies, discussion groups, readings, and group activities, students learn how economists define and analyze environmental problems and the types of policies they advocate for managing environmental quality. CROSSLISTED as AEC 352/ECON 352. (Bacc Core Course)', 'Prerequisites: AEC 250, AREC 250, ECON 201 or 201H.A minimum grade of D- is required in AEC 250, AREC 250, ECON 201 and ECON 201H.'),
(1850, '4', '*THE ECONOMICS OF DISCRIMINATION', 'ECON 383', 0, 'An economic analysis of discrimination, focusing on labor market inequities for women and minorities. Historical and current trends in pay, education, and employment disparities, economic explanations for such disparities, and econometric evidence for wage and employment discrimination. (SS) (Bacc Core Course)', 'Prerequisites: ECON 201 or 201H.A minimum grade of C- is required in ECON 201 and ECON 201H.Enrollment limited to students in the Dist. Degree Corvallis Student or Oregon State - Cascades campuses.'),
