(1857, '4', 'ADVANCED MICROECONOMIC THEORY', 'ECON 411', 0, 'Rigorous treatment of optimizing behavior of economic agents and markets. Examines utility maximization and demand; cost minimization, profit maximization and supply; perfect competition and monopoly; imperfect competition and game theory; and general equilibrium, social welfare and market failure using sophisticated mathematical tools. Students cannot receive credit toward the major for both ECON 311 and ECON 411.', 'Prerequisites: (ECON 201 or 201H) and (MTH 241, 251 or 251H).A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 201, ECON 201H, MTH 241, MTH 251 and MTH 251H.'),
(1858, '4', 'ADVANCED MACROECONOMIC THEORY', 'ECON 415', 0, 'Macroeconomics as an application of general equilibrium theory. Macroeconomic models are developed taking preferences and technology as primitives. The models\' short and long run predictions are analyzed and compared to the data. The welfare implications of fiscal and monetary policy are discussed. ECON 315 and ECON 415 cannot both be taken for credit toward the major.', 'Prerequisites: (ECON 201 or 201H) and (ECON 202 or 202H) and (MTH 241, 251 or 251H).A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 201, ECON 201H, ECON 202, ECON 202H, MTH 241, MTH 251 and MTH 251H.'),
(1859, '4', 'GAME THEORY', 'ECON 420', 0, 'Systematically studies strategic interactions among multiple decision makers with applications in economics, politics, sociology, law, computer science, sports, and biology. Topics taught include static, sequential, and repeated games of perfect and imperfect information.', 'Prerequisites: ECON 311 or 411.A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 311 and ECON 411.'),
(1860, '4', 'PRE-ECONOMETRICS', 'ECON 423', 0, 'Introduction to probability and statistics with an emphasis on estimation and hypothesis testing. Applications to economic models.', 'Prerequisites: MTH 241, 251 or 251H.A minimum grade of D- is required in MTH 241, MTH 251 and MTH 251H.'),
(1861, '4', 'INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMETRICS', 'ECON 424', 0, 'Application of statistical techniques, including sampling theory, hypothesis testing, and multiple regression analysis, to economic models. Economic modeling, analysis of economic data, and policy analysis are emphasized. ECON 424 and ECON 427 cannot both be taken for credit toward the major. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisites: (ECON 311 or 411) and (ST 351, 351H or ECON 423).A minimum grade of C is required in ECON 311, ECON 411, ST 351, ST 351H and ECON 423.'),
(1862, '4', 'INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMETRICS WITH CALCULUS', 'ECON 427', 0, 'Addresses both the theory and practice of econometrics, including properties of estimators, modeling economic processes, estimation, hypothesis testing, prediction and interpretation of results. Students cannot receive credit toward the major for both ECON 424 and ECON 427. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisites: (ECON 311 or 411) and ECON 423.A minimum grade of C is required in ECON 311, ECON 411 and ECON 423.'),
(1863, '4', '^INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMIC RESEARCH', 'ECON 428', 0, 'Basic methods of economic research: concepts and models; data sources, collection, and presentation; hypothesis formulation and testing; policy analysis. Written assignments apply methods. (Writing Intensive Course)', 'Prerequisites: ECON 311 or 411.A minimum grade of C- is required in ECON 311 and ECON 411.'),
(1864, '4', 'PUBLIC ECONOMICS', 'ECON 435', 0, 'Composition and growth of government spending; theory of public expenditure; analysis of public expenditure programs; benefit-cost analysis; theory and practice of taxation; analysis of local, state, and federal taxes; government borrowing and fees; current issues in tax and expenditure policy.', 'Prerequisites: ECON 311 or 411.A minimum grade of C- is required in ECON 311 and ECON 411.'),
(1865, '4', '^PUBLIC POLICY ANALYSIS', 'ECON 439', 0, 'Theory of public problems and decision making. Evaluation of public policy strategies, selected public programs and individual public projects considering the full range of efficiency and equity effects. Direct and indirect impacts of policy, strength of implicit incentives, administrative feasibility, and problems of policy implementation. (Writing Intensive Course)', 'Prerequisites: ECON 311 or 411.A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 311 and ECON 411.'),
(1866, '4', 'INTERNATIONAL FINANCE THEORY AND POLICY', 'ECON 441', 0, 'Theories and policies of exchange rate regimes; fixed, floating and managed floats; internal and external trade and capital balances; international capital flows and institutions.', 'Prerequisite: ECON 315.A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 315.'),
(1867, '4', 'ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT', 'ECON 455', 0, 'History, theories and policies for economic development in the Third World of underdeveloped countries. (SS)', 'Prerequisites: ECON 201 and 202.A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 201 and ECON 202.'),
(1868, '4', 'INDUSTRIAL ORGANIZATION THEORY AND POLICY', 'ECON 460', 0, 'The study of the causes of market structure, the behavior of firms in game theoretic settings, and the welfare implications of competitive and imperfectly competitive markets; United States antitrust and other laws regulating business behavior.', 'Prerequisites: ECON 311 or 411.A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 311 and ECON 411.'),
(1869, '4', 'LAW, ECONOMICS, AND REGULATION', 'ECON 461', 0, 'The analysis of the effectiveness of laws and government regulations in fostering economic efficiency and fairness. Topics include the design of laws and policies to promote social welfare and the study of the effectiveness of criminal law, antitrust law, and the government regulation of business in promoting social goals.', 'Prerequisites: ECON 201 or 201H.A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 201 and ECON 201H.'),
(1870, '4', 'MANAGERIAL ECONOMICS', 'ECON 462', 0, 'The application of microeconomic theory and quantitative methods to management decisions. Case-oriented course emphasizing actual business decisions.', 'Prerequisites: ECON 311 or 411.A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 311 and ECON 411.'),
(1871, '4', 'LABOR ECONOMICS AND SOCIAL POLICY', 'ECON 480', 0, 'Interaction of workers and firms in labor markets, social policy and its effects on labor markets, human capital theory and education policy, discrimination and other sources of wage differentials, immigration, unemployment, inequality.', 'Prerequisites: ECON 311 or 411.A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 311 and ECON 411.'),
(1872, '4', 'ECONOMICS OF INEQUALITY', 'ECON 491', 0, 'An analysis of economic inequality. Describing and measuring inequality, historical and current trends in inequality, causes and consequences of inequality, and policy implications.', 'Prerequisites: ECON 311 or 411.A minimum grade of D- is required in ECON 311 and ECON 411.Enrollment limited to students in the Dist. Degree Corvallis Student or Oregon State - Cascades campuses.'),
