(2398, '3', '*INTRODUCTION TO FILM STUDIES: 1895-1945', 'FILM 110', 0, 'An introduction to the serious study of world cinema, 1895-1945. Class lectures will offer a variety of  historical, critical and theoretical approaches. Weekly screenings of important films from the U.S., Europe, and Asia accompany the lectures. Film fee required. (H) (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(2399, '3', '*INTRODUCTION TO FILM STUDIES: 1945-PRESENT', 'FILM 125', 0, 'Provides an introduction to the serious study of world cinema, 1945-present. Class lectures will offer a variety of historical, critical and theoretical approaches. Weekly screenings of important films from the U.S., Europe, and Asia accompany the lectures. Film fee required. (H) (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(2400, '4', '*TOPICS IN DIFF, POWER, & DISC: *T/DF,PWR,DS:SEXUALITY IN FILM', 'FILM 220', 0, 'A comparative treatment of literary topics in the context of institutional and systematic discrimination. Not offered every year. CROSSLISTED as ENG 220/FILM 220. (H) (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(2401, '4', '*TOPICS IN DIFF, POWER, & DISC: *TOPICS/ AFRICA IN HOLLYWOOD', 'FILM 220', 0, 'A comparative treatment of literary topics in the context of institutional and systematic discrimination. Not offered every year. CROSSLISTED as ENG 220/FILM 220. (H) (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(2402, '4', '*TOPICS IN DIFFERENCE, POWER, AND DISCRIMINATION', 'FILM 220', 0, 'A comparative treatment of literary topics in the context of institutional and systematic discrimination. Not offered every year. CROSSLISTED as ENG 220/FILM 220. (H) (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(2403, '4', '*THE NEW AMERICAN CINEMA', 'FILM 245', 0, 'A formalist, ideological, and commercial investigation into contemporary American cinema. Three hours of lecture and separate screenings each week. Film fee required. Not offered every year. (H) (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(2404, '4', '*WORLD CINEMA PART II: 1968-PRESENT', 'FILM 256', 0, 'A systematic introduction to the arts and history of international cinema, from the decolonization movement in the 1960s and the 1970s to the dynamics of globalization that we are experiencing today. Weekly screenings include such films as A Better Tomorrow, Chungking Express, Spirited Away, Oldboy, Bombay, and City of God. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(2405, '4', '*FILMS FOR THE FUTURE', 'FILM 265', 0, 'An interdisciplinary study of film, literary, and philosophical visions of the future. Three hours of lecture and separate screenings each week. Film fee required. Not offered every year. (H) (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(2406, '4', 'DOCUMENTARY FILM STUDIES', 'FILM 445', 0, 'Examines the worldwide development of documentary filmmaking. We interrogate the nature, form, and function of non-fiction cinematic forms by analyzing diverse films, filmmakers, and theoretical models, while paying attention to social, technological, and aesthetic influences. We study significant modes of documentary including the city symphony, political documentary, direct cinema/cinema verite, and postmodern documentary. Finally, we will pay special attention to the cross-fertilization of non-fiction with other filmmaking modes. Throughout the course, we seek to answer the following questions: How do documentary conventions mark the \"Real\"? How is documentary film a tool for social change?', ''),
(2407, '4', 'STUDIES IN FILM, CULT & SOCTY: ST/ FILM NOIR', 'FILM 480', 0, 'Study of film in its relationship to society and culture; study of film culture. Topics change from term to term. (H)', ''),
(2408, '4', 'STUDIES IN FILM, CULT & SOCTY: ST/ MEDICINE AND MEDIA', 'FILM 480', 0, 'Study of film in its relationship to society and culture; study of film culture. Topics change from term to term. (H)', ''),
(2409, '4', 'STUDIES IN FILM: ST/ROAD TRIP TO NOWHERE:CC', 'FILM 552', 2, 'Particular cinematographers, movements, types, conventions, or problems in film. Topics change from term to term. Lecture and separate screenings each week. Film fee required. Not offered every year.', ''),
(2410, '4', 'STUDIES IN FILM, CULT & SOCTY: ST/ FILM NOIR', 'FILM 580', 2, 'Study of film in its relationship to society and culture; study of film culture. Topics change from term to term.', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:History of Science (5440)Women, Gender, and Sexuality (8008)Environmental Arts & Humanitie (8200)Women Studies (8680)English (8900)Creative Writing (8920)Applied Ethics (9580)Interdisciplinary Studies (9900)'),
(2411, '4', 'INVESTMENTS', 'FIN 341', 0, 'Risk and reward characteristics of investments; sources of investment information; domestic and international security markets; investment characteristics of common stocks, debt securities, convertible securities, option contracts, and investment companies; real property investment; economic market analysis; technical market analysis; tax aspects of investments; and investment management.', 'Prerequisites: BA 240, 240H, 360, 360H, FIN 340 or 340H.A minimum grade of C is required in BA 240, BA 240H, BA 360, BA 360H, FIN 340 and FIN 340H.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182) or Finance (813).'),
(2412, '4', 'ADVANCED FINANCIAL MANAGEMENT', 'FIN 342', 0, 'Capital market theory and the valuation of risky assets, capital budgeting, valuing the firm\'s securities, capital structure theory, long-term financing alternatives, cost of capital, dividend policy, working capital management, financial analysis and planning, mergers, and takeovers.', 'Prerequisites: FIN 340, 340H, BA 240, 240H, 360 or 360H.A minimum grade of C is required in FIN 340, FIN 340H, BA 240, BA 240H, BA 360 and BA 360H.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182), Industrial Engineering (323), Business Engineering (355) or Finance (813).'),
(2413, '2 to 4', 'CFA PREPARATION', 'FIN 434', 0, 'Provides students with structure and guidance in their preparation for the Chartered Financial Analyst (CFA) Level exam. Students systematically prepare for and are tested on the 18 sections of the exam.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182).'),
(2414, '2', 'APPLIED PORTFOLIO MANAGEMENT', 'FIN 437', 0, 'Hands-on experience of managing two investment portfolios. Each member in the Oregon State Investment Group (OSIG) should act as a financial analyst to analyze a chosen company by performing the  Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) or Residual Income Model (RIM), the relative valuation, and the SWOT analyses. The weekly seminar offers opportunities for students to present their analyses and offer comments and suggestions to other\'s presentations.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182).'),
(2415, '1', 'APPLIED PORTFOLIO MANAGEMENT II', 'FIN 438', 0, 'Each student will act as a financial analyst to analyze a chosen company using models learned in FIN 437. Provides students with an opportunity to practice security valuation and get familiar with the tools. In addition, this course will focus on various measures of portfolio performance.', 'Prerequisites: FIN 437 or BA 437.A minimum grade of C- is required in FIN 437 and BA 437.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182).'),
(2416, '1', 'APPLIED PORTFOLIO MANAGEMENT III', 'FIN 439', 0, 'Each student will act as a financial analyst to analyze a chosen company using models learned from FIN 437. Provides students additional opportunity to practice security valuation and strengthen their understanding of the tools. In addition, this course will introduce ways to develop an efficient portfolio.', 'Prerequisites: FIN 437 or BA 437.A minimum grade of C- is required in FIN 437 and BA 437.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182).'),
(2417, '4', 'FIXED INCOME SECURITIES', 'FIN 440', 0, 'Provides students with intermediate knowledge of fixed income assets, interest rate and interest rate theory, the tools for estimating values, and managing portfolios of fixed income assets. The course can also serve as a partial coverage of material expected of applicants planning on seeking the Certified Financial Analyst designation.', 'Prerequisite: FIN 341.A minimum grade of C- is required in FIN 341.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182) or Finance (813).'),
(2418, '4', 'FINANCIAL INSTITUTIONS', 'FIN 441', 0, 'Introduction of markets and institutions that form the economic system of trading financial and real assets both domestically and internationally. The introduction of concepts of financial theory, institutional detail, regulatory environments, and the history of financial markets. Topics include legal, ethical, technological, and global issues facing financial managers, markets, and institutions.', 'Prerequisites: BA 240, 240H, 360, 360H, FIN 340 or 340H.A minimum grade of C is required in BA 240, BA 240H, BA 360, BA 360H, FIN 340 and FIN 340H.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182) or Finance (813).'),
(2419, '4', 'FINANCIAL STATEMENT ANALYSIS', 'FIN 442', 0, 'Student develop the understanding and skill to use financial statements for investment decisions, credit decisions, performance analysis, and forecasting. Three main topic areas: analysis overview, accounting analysis, and financial analysis.', 'Prerequisite: FIN 342.A minimum grade of C- is required in FIN 342.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182) or Finance (813).'),
(2420, '4', 'PORTFOLIO MANAGEMENT', 'FIN 443', 0, 'An introduction to the construction, revision, and performance evaluation of financial asset portfolios.', 'Prerequisites: FIN 341 or BA 341.A minimum grade of C- is required in FIN 341 and BA 341.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182) or Finance (813).'),
(2421, '4', 'FINANCIAL RISK MANAGEMENT', 'FIN 444', 0, 'Investigation of financial hedging activities for corporations and financial institutions using futures, options, and other derivative securities. Identification of risk attributes, valid hedging rationales, and management of hedging programs.', 'Prerequisite: FIN 341.A minimum grade of C- is required in FIN 341.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182) or Finance (813).'),
(2422, '4', 'INTERNATIONAL FINANCIAL MANAGEMENT', 'FIN 445', 0, 'International monetary environment; foreign exchange risk management; source and availability of funds to finance trade and multinational operations; taxation planning and control; international portfolio diversification; international banking; capital budgeting; political risk evaluation of performance.', 'Prerequisites: FIN 341 and 342 and (FIN 440, 442, 443, 444 or 499).A minimum grade of C- is required in FIN 341, FIN 342, FIN 440, FIN 442, FIN 443, FIN 444 and FIN 499.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182) or Finance (813).'),
(2423, '4', 'SELECTED TOPICS IN FINANCE: ST/ ADVANCED CORPORATE FINANCE', 'FIN 499', 0, 'Examination of the impact of recent advances in finance on contemporary business. Topic will vary from term to term.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182) or Finance (813).'),
(2424, '4', 'SELECTED TOPICS IN FINANCE: ST/ COMMERCIAL BANKING', 'FIN 499', 0, 'Examination of the impact of recent advances in finance on contemporary business. Topic will vary from term to term.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182) or Finance (813).'),
(2425, '4', 'SELECTED TOPICS IN FINANCE: ST/PRINCIPLES OF FIN PLANNING', 'FIN 499', 0, 'Examination of the impact of recent advances in finance on contemporary business. Topic will vary from term to term.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Finance (182) or Finance (813).'),
(2426, '3', 'INVESTMENTS', 'FIN 542', 2, 'Introduction to the tools and concepts of security analysis and investments; basic security types, including stocks, bonds, options and futures, respective markets and to how these securities are traded; fundamental valuation techniques and theory for stocks and bonds.', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Corporate Finance (2063) or Financial Planning (CG16).'),
(2427, '4', 'PORTFOLIO MANAGEMENT', 'FIN 543', 2, 'An introduction to the construction, revision, and performance evaluation of financial asset portfolios.', 'Prerequisite: FIN 542.A minimum grade of C is required in FIN 542.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Corporate Finance (2063).'),
(2428, '4', 'FINANCIAL RISK MANAGEMENT', 'FIN 544', 2, 'Investigation of financial hedging activities for corporations and financial institutions using futures, options, and other derivative securities. Identification of risk attributes, valid hedging rationales, and management of hedging programs.', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Corporate Finance (2063).'),
(2429, '3', 'ADVANCED CORPORATE FINANCE', 'FIN 546', 2, 'The second course in the Corporate Finance sequence. Examines corporate payout policies and capital structure choices, choices in debt financing, financial planning and working capital management, and valuation of projects using a real-options approach.', 'Prerequisite: BA 540.A minimum grade of B- is required in BA 540.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Corporate Finance (2063).'),
(2430, '3', 'MERGERS AND ACQUISITIONS', 'FIN 549', 2, 'Provides an in-depth examination of the theory and practice of the market for corporate control, primarily focusing on mergers and acquisitions (M&amp;A). The objective of the course is to provide an understanding of how to structure, value, and implement an M&amp;A transaction. Students will be expected to apply the appropriate tools and skills to evaluate M&amp;A transactions.', 'Prerequisite: FIN 546.A minimum grade of B- is required in FIN 546.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Corporate Finance (2063).'),
(2431, '4', 'SELECTED TOPICS IN FINANCE: ST/ FIXED INCOME SECURITIES', 'FIN 599', 2, '', ''),
(2432, '1', 'ORIENTATION TO FISHERIES AND WILDLIFE', 'FW 107', 0, 'Information relevant to academic pathways and career planning in the fields of fisheries and wildlife. Graded P/N.', ''),
(2433, '1', 'INTRODUCTION TO MARINE LIFE IN THE SEA-MARINE BIRDS AND MAMMALS', 'FW 113', 0, 'Introduces first- and second-year undergraduates, teachers and non-degree students to the breadth of marine science course offerings and research at Oregon State University?s Hatfield Marine Science Center located in Newport, Oregon. Using an experiential based format, students collect field data to better understand marine mammals (whales, dolphins and porpoises), seabirds, and their interactions with their environment. Lec/lab. Graded P/N.', 'Enrollment is limited to Postbac Degree Seeking or Undergraduate level students.'),
(2434, '1', 'SPECIAL STUDIES: SS/ INTRODUCTION TO SHARKS', 'FW 199', 0, 'Graded P/N.', ''),
(2435, '1', 'CAREER SKILLS IN FISHERIES AND WILDLIFE SCIENCES', 'FW 209', 0, 'A foundation for life-long career development in fisheries and wildlife sciences. Practice the skills needed to search, apply, and attain internships and jobs.', 'Prerequisite: FW 107.A minimum grade of P is required in FW 107.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Fisheries and Wildlife Science (133) or Fisheries & Wildlife Sciences (733).'),
(2436, '3', 'PRINCIPLES OF FISH AND WILDLIFE CONSERVATION', 'FW 251', 0, 'History of conservation and natural resource use; ecological principles, and social and economic limitations of conservation; principles and practices of wildlife and fisheries management; role of research in management.', ''),
(2437, '3', 'FIELD SAMPLING OF FISH AND WILDLIFE', 'FW 255', 0, 'Introduction to sampling populations and communities of vertebrate animals emphasizing sampling design, collection and management of data, and communication of results.', ''),
(2438, '4', 'COMMUNICATION SKILLS FOR FISHERIES AND WILDLIFE PROFESSIONALS', 'FW 289', 0, 'Introduces students to the theoretical and practical dimensions of interpersonal and public communication in a natural resource management field. Lec/rec.', ''),
(2439, '1', 'FIELD TECHNIQUES FOR MARINE MAMMAL CONSERVATION', 'FW 301', 0, 'A laboratory and hands-on experience covering field techniques, computer software for data organization and analyses, and understanding the practical management conservation application for students who are taking or have taken FW/BI 302, Biology and Conservation of Marine Mammals. Taught summer term at HMSC, Newport, OR.', 'Prerequisites: BI 302* or FW 302*.* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of D- is required in BI 302 and FW 302.'),
(2440, '4', 'BIOLOGY AND CONSERVATION OF MARINE MAMMALS', 'FW 302', 0, 'An examination of the biology of whales, pinnipeds, and other marine mammals, including general adaptations to a marine existence; systematics and biogeography; reproduction; diving physiology; communication and echolocation; feeding and migratory behavior; and marine mammal/human interactions; including conservation issues. Taught at Hatfield Marine Science Center OR online through Ecampus.', ''),
(2441, '3', 'SURVEY OF GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION SYSTEMS IN NATURAL RESOURCE', 'FW 303', 0, 'Concepts underlying geographic information systems, global positioning system, and remote sensing; application to management and research, data quality issues, and case studies. Not a lab/skills class.', ''),
(2442, '1', 'SPECIALIZATION DEVELOPMENT', 'FW 307', 0, 'Students will examine career alternatives, develop career goals, learn what knowledge, skills, and abilities are important for diverse careers in fisheries and wildlife conservation, and develop an academic and lifelong plan for achieving their career goals. This course is intended to assist students in developing a specialization in fisheries and wildlife sciences. Graded P/N.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a major in Fisheries and Wildlife Science (133) or Fisheries & Wildlife Sciences (733).'),
(2443, '3', 'ORNITHOLOGY', 'FW 311', 0, 'Survey of the adaptations of birds to a diverse array of habitats. Topics include origins, anatomy, reproductive strategies, migration, flight, behavior, physiology, nutrition, and conservation.', ''),
(2444, '2', 'SYSTEMATICS OF BIRDS', 'FW 312', 0, 'External anatomy, classification of birds of the world, and field identification of birds by sight and song. Field trips required.', ''),
(2445, '3', 'ICHTHYOLOGY', 'FW 315', 0, 'A survey of the diversity of biological adaptations of fishes. Topics include physiological and zoogeographical adaptations, reproduction, evolution, cladogenesis, morphology, behavior, and genetics.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
(2446, '3', 'SYSTEMATICS OF FISHES', 'FW 316', 0, 'Phylogenetic diversity, evolution, relationships and identification of the world\'s fishes, with particular focus on Oregon fishes. Includes identification, anatomy, use of keys, introduction to the comparative method, systematic theory, taxonomy, field collection and specimen curation. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 211, 211H or 204) and (BI 212, 212H or 205) and (BI 213, 213H or 206).A minimum grade of D- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 204, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 205, BI 213, BI 213H and BI 206.'),
(2447, '3', 'MAMMALOGY', 'FW 317', 0, 'A survey of the origins, evolution, diversity, and adaptations of mammals to diverse environments. Topics include taxonomy, reproduction, sensory perception, herbivory, population cycles and behavior.', ''),
(2448, '2', 'SYSTEMATICS OF MAMMALS', 'FW 318', 0, 'A survey of the phylogenetic diversity of the mammals in Oregon from a habitat/community perspective. Identifying, using keys, and measuring specimens will be stressed.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
(2449, '4', 'INTRODUCTORY POPULATION DYNAMICS', 'FW 320', 0, 'Principles and concepts of population dynamics related to fish and wildlife populations; methods of estimating abundance, mortality, sustainable harvest levels and extinction risk; hands-on introduction to models for population analysis. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisites: BI 370*, 370H* or 371*.* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of D- is required in BI 370, BI 370H and BI 371.'),
(2450, '3', 'APPLIED COMMUNITY AND ECOSYSTEM ECOLOGY', 'FW 321', 0, 'Perspectives in community and ecosystem ecology, and their use in management of fisheries and wildlife resource systems.', 'Prerequisite: FW 320*.* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of D- is required in FW 320.'),
(2451, '3', 'MANAGEMENT PRINCIPLES OF PACIFIC SALMON IN THE NORTHWEST', 'FW 323', 0, 'Explores the nature of the salmon problem in the Northwest. Experts from diverse disciplines describe principles of salmon biology, habitat ecology and management, socioeconomics of direct and indirect users, and government policies.', ''),
(2452, '3', '*FOOD FROM THE SEA', 'FW 324', 0, 'Where does seafood come from, and how does seafood arrive on a plate? How productive are the world?s oceans, and can the oceans continue to produce enough to feed (and employ) the masses? How do different cultures, ethnicities, and regions of the world rely upon food from the sea for daily meals? Food from the Sea is an exploration of the cultural, societal, economic, practical, and environmental features of the protein that feeds billions. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(2453, '3', '*GLOBAL CRISES IN RESOURCE ECOLOGY', 'FW 325', 0, 'Historical and contemporary implications of the impacts of burgeoning human populations on rates and patterns of global ecological change. Changes in ecosystem processes and crises of species extinction in the context of cultural and political institutions. (Bacc Core Course).', ''),
(2454, '3', 'INTEGRATED WATERSHED MANAGEMENT', 'FW 326', 0, 'A comprehensive approach to watershed management, one that includes biophysical, socioeconomic, planning and education related topics. Intended for students interested in the sustainable management of natural resources.', ''),
(2455, '2', 'WILDLIFE CAPTURE AND IMMOBILIZATION', 'FW 328', 0, 'Manual and chemical restraint methods are covered with an emphasis on darting equipment, animal and human safety, drug pharmacology and species specific recommendations.', ''),
(2456, '4', 'ECOLOGY OF MARINE AND ESTUARINE BIRDS', 'FW 331', 0, 'Focusing on how marine and estuarine birds are adapted for life at sea. Topics include morphology, physiology, foraging ecology, and biogeography as well as introductory oceanography. Field trips.', ''),
(2457, '3', '*MULTICULTURAL PERSPECTIVES IN NATURAL RESOURCES', 'FW 340', 0, 'Explores multicultural influences on development of natural resources in the American West. Effects of diverse social values on changes in the physical landscape and biodiversity. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(2458, '2', 'FISH AND WILDLIFE LAW ENFORCEMENT', 'FW 341', 0, 'Introduction to the philosophy, purposes, and methods of enforcing natural resource laws, emphasizing fish and wildlife laws.', ''),
(2459, '3', '*ENDANGERED SPECIES, SOCIETY AND SUSTAINABILITY', 'FW 350', 0, 'Provides a general background to endangered species biology, and the social and economic implications of the legislation enacted to conserve endangered species (Endangered Species Act, CITES Treaty). (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(2460, '3', '*CITIZEN SCIENCE', 'FW 356', 0, 'Citizen science involves non-specialists in scientific studies addressing large challenges best solved through collaboration. Citizens contribute data scientists may not otherwise be able to obtain, while improving their understanding of the scientific process, integrating technology into the learning process, and generating new knowledge for society. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(2461, '3', '*ORIGINS OF F&W MANAGEMENT-EVOLUTION, GENETICS, AND ECOLOGY', 'FW 360', 0, 'Examines genetics and human interactions with fisheries and wildlife from an ecological and evolutionary perspective. Basic principles of environmental interactions, and how humans interact with other species and their environments in the disciplines commonly recognized as fisheries, wildlife and conservation sciences. (Baccalaureate Core Course)', ''),
(2462, '3', '*ORIGINS OF F&W MANAGEMENT: *ORIGINS FW MGT: EVOL,GEN,ECOL', 'FW 360', 0, 'Examines genetics and human interactions with fisheries and wildlife from an ecological and evolutionary perspective. Basic principles of environmental interactions, and how humans interact with other species and their environments in the disciplines commonly recognized as fisheries, wildlife and conservation sciences. (Baccalaureate Core Course)', ''),
(2463, '3', 'ENVIRONMENTAL CONTAMINANTS IN FISH AND WILDLIFE', 'FW 366', 0, 'Environmental contamination is an important threat to many fish and wildlife populations and the habitats and prey upon which they rely. The field of ecotoxicology links the ecology of fish and wildlife with toxicology of environmental contaminants, and so spans political, scientific, and public relations realms. Through the pairing of introductory concepts with key case studies, this course provides students with a preparatory framework for understanding toxicological issues of importance for those focused on studying, managing or conserving fish and wildlife populations.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 204, 211 or 211H) and (BI 205, 212 or 212H).A minimum grade of D- is required in BI 204, BI 211, BI 211H, BI 205, BI 212 and BI 212H.'),
(2464, '4', 'CONSERVATION GENETICS', 'FW 370', 0, 'A foundational course in preparation for a degree in Fisheries and Wildlife or other degrees focused on conservation of natural resources. Covers a broad range of topics associated with issues surrounding genetics that working professionals in the biological sciences should be conversant about. One of the most important aspects of the course is the development of problem-solving and critical-thinking skills.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 211 or 204) and (BI 212 or 205) and (BI 213 or 206).A minimum grade of D- is required in BI 211, BI 204, BI 212, BI 205, BI 213 and BI 206.'),
