(2815, '3', 'INTRODUCTION TO FORESTRY', 'FOR 111', 0, 'Forest resources in the world; forests and human well-being; where and how forests grow; environmental and human values; products, characteristics, and uses; basic elements of use, planning and management. Interpretation of forestry literature; professional origins in the U.S. Field trips required.', ''),
(2816, '3', 'COMPUTING APPLICATIONS IN FORESTRY', 'FOR 112', 0, 'An overview of computing applications used in all aspects of forestry work, but largely focused on development of intermediate and advanced spreadsheet skills using Microsoft Excel (e.g., complex formulas and functions, charting, and pivot tables). Additionally, the course rounds out essential skills in document formatting and presentation development.', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Renewable Materials (238)Forest Management (385)Recreation Resource Management (460)Pre-Forestry (810)Tourism, Rec, & Adventure Lead (872)INTO OSU GE/AE/Pathways or Non-Degree / Credential level students may not enroll.'),
(2817, '1', '*FOREST SOILS LABORATORY FOR SOIL 205', 'FOR 206', 0, 'Laboratory exercise and field trips designed to develop student competency in soil processes, description, analysis, and assessment with a particular emphasis on the role of soils in managed and unmanaged forest ecosystems. (Bacc Core Course if taken with SOIL 205)', 'INTO OSU GE/AE/Pathways or Non-Degree / Credential level students may not enroll.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Forestry or Pre-Forestry Program colleges.'),
(2818, '1', 'FOREST SOILS RECITATION', 'FOR 208', 0, 'Readings, exercises, discussions designed to develop student competency in forest soil processes, description, analysis, and assessment. A particular emphasis will be placed on the role of soils in managed and unmanaged forest ecosystems.', ''),
(2819, '2', 'FORESTRY FIELD SCHOOL', 'FOR 312', 0, 'A hands-on experience in the major aspects of forestry, including regeneration surveys, silviculture, cruising, recreation, forest disturbances, logging site and mill visits, east and west of the Cascades Range. CROSSLISTED as FE 312/FOR 312.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Civil Engineering (306), Forest Engineering (380), Forest - Civil Engineering (381) or Forestry (820).Graduate, INTO OSU GE/AE/Pathways or Non-Degree / Credential level students may not enroll.'),
(2820, '5', 'FOREST MENSURATION', 'FOR 321', 0, 'Theory and practice of sampling and cruising techniques; stratified and nonstratified sampling systems with fixed plots, variable plots, and 3-P designs.', 'Prerequisites: (FOR 141, FES 141, FOR 241 or FES 241) and FE 208 and 209 and (MTH 241, 245, 251 or 251H) and (ST 201, 314, 314H, 351 or 351H).A minimum grade of C is required in FOR 141, FES 141, FOR 241, FES 241, FE 208, FE 209, MTH 241, MTH 245, MTH 251, MTH 251H, ST 201, ST 314, ST 314H, ST 351 and ST 351H.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Forest Engineering (380)Forest - Civil Engineering (381)Forest Management (385)Recreation Resource Management (460)Forest Operations Management (623)Natural Resources (643)Natural Resources (671)Forestry (706)Forestry (820)INTO OSU GE/AE/Pathways or Non-Degree / Credential level students may not enroll.Students in the Pre-Forestry Program college may not enroll.'),
(2821, '3', 'FOREST MODELS', 'FOR 322', 0, 'Introduction to static and dynamic forest models: defining what they are, how they might be used, and, in general terms, how they are developed.', 'Prerequisites: FOR 321 and MTH 241 and (ST 201 or 351).A minimum grade of C- is required in FOR 321.A minimum grade of D- is required in MTH 241, ST 201 and ST 351.INTO OSU GE/AE/Pathways or Non-Degree / Credential level students may not enroll.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Forestry college.'),
(2822, '4', 'FOREST RESOURCE ECONOMICS I', 'FOR 330', 0, 'Basic arithmetic of interest and capital budgeting. Basic wood products markets. Forest resource markets and market failures. Nonmarket valuation and multiple-use forestry. Impacts of forest management and policy decisions on forest resource use. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisites: (AEC 250, AREC 250, ECON 201 or 201H) and (MTH 241, 245, 251, 251H, 252 or 252H).A minimum grade of C is required in AEC 250, AREC 250, ECON 201, ECON 201H, MTH 241, MTH 245, MTH 251, MTH 251H, MTH 252 and MTH 252H.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Fisheries and Wildlife Science (133)Civil Engineering (306)Forest Engineering (380)Forest - Civil Engineering (381)Ecological Engineering (450)Recreation Resource Management (460)Bioenergy (497)Natural Resources (643)Natural Resources (671)Forestry (706)Fisheries & Wildlife Sciences (733)Bioenergy (767)Bioproducts (768)Forestry (820)INTO OSU GE/AE/Pathways or Non-Degree / Credential level students may not enroll.'),
(2823, '4', 'FOREST RESOURCE ECONOMICS II', 'FOR 331', 0, 'Forest products markets, appraisal, rotation, thinning, uneven-aged management and forest regulation. Economics of timber management and harvest scheduling.', 'Prerequisites: ST 201 or 351.A minimum grade of C is required in ST 201 and ST 351.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Environmental Economics (250)Forest Engineering (380)Recreation Resource Management (460)Environmental Sciences (657)Forestry (706)Bioenergy (767)Bioproducts (768)Forestry (820)INTO OSU GE/AE/Pathways or Non-Degree / Credential level students may not enroll.'),
(2824, '3', 'TOPICS IN WILDLAND FIRE', 'FOR 346', 0, 'An interdisciplinary survey of concepts relating to fire science, ecology, management, and policy. Includes case studies of several representative ecosystems, ranging from west- and eastside forests of the Pacific Northwest to shrub steppe ecosystems of the Intermountain West and chaparral ecosystems of southern California. Distance and campus-based delivery using videos, website, and discussion.', 'INTO OSU GE/AE/Pathways or Non-Degree / Credential level students may not enroll.'),
