(2841, '4', '^FOREST POLICY', 'FOR 460', 0, 'Policy formulation and analysis for forest resources. Consideration of policy affecting land management approaches to planning, management, and social and economic development. Major forestry policy areas covered include outdoor recreation, range, timber, wilderness, and wildlife and fish. Lec/lab. (Writing Intensive Course)', 'Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Forest Engineering (380)Forest Management (385)Recreation Resource Management (460)Forest Operations Management (623)Natural Resources (643)Natural Resources (671)Forestry (706)Forestry (820)Tourism, Rec, & Adventure Lead (872)INTO OSU GE/AE/Pathways or Non-Degree / Credential level students may not enroll.Students in the Pre-Forestry Program college may not enroll.'),
(2842, '3', 'NATURAL RESOURCE POLICY AND LAW', 'FOR 462', 0, 'First of two offerings designed to provide an introduction to current environmental and natural resource law issues and disputes for students who will have to meet, consult, and work with lawyers throughout their professional career. Focus is on mechanisms governing resource allocation within the constraints of private property rights. Emphasis is placed on the federal Endangered Species Act and its relation to water allocation and public trust doctrines. Students will also gain a broad understanding of regulatory', ''),
(2843, '4', 'FOREST MANAGEMENT PLANNING AND DESIGN II', 'FOR 469', 0, 'A team-based, project-centric course for integrated timber harvest planning. Establish tactical and operational planning goals and constraints, identify feasible harvesting and transportation systems, and design harvest units to meet objectives and constraints. Lec/lab. CROSSLISTED as FE 469/FOR 469.', 'Prerequisites: FE 459 or FOR 459.A minimum grade of C is required in FE 459 and FOR 459.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Forest Engineering (380), Forest Operations Management (623) or Forestry (820).INTO OSU GE/AE/Pathways or Non-Degree / Credential level students may not enroll.'),
(2844, '3', 'SPECIAL TOPICS: ST/FIRE RISK ASSMT MAP & TOOLS', 'FOR 499', 0, 'Topics of current importance in forest resources issues, education, policies, economics, management, business, social values, silviculture, and biometrics. Topics will change from term to term. May be repeated with different topics for credit. Section 8: Social aspects of natural resource management (3 credits) graded.', ''),
