(2944, '1 to 15', 'INTERNSHIP', 'GEOG 510', 2, 'Pre-career professional experience under joint faculty and employer supervision. Graded P/N.', ''),
(2945, '3', 'HISTORY AND PHILOSOPHY OF GEOGRAPHY', 'GEOG 511', 2, 'The historical development of research traditions in the discipline of geography. This includes an examination of changes in conceptual structures and current trends. Equivalent course is GEO 515.', ''),
(2946, '3', 'SOCIAL-ECOLOGICAL SYSTEMS', 'GEOG 512', 2, 'Exploration of critical debates surrounding theories associated with social-ecological systems, resilience, vulnerability, adaptation, social learning, transformation, adaptive governance. Equivalent course is GEO 554.', ''),
(2947, '3', 'HYDROLOGY FOR WATER RESOURCES MANAGEMENT', 'GEOG 524', 2, 'A quantitative introduction to surface and subsurface hydrology with a focus on decision making for the water resource professional.', ''),
(2948, '3', 'WATER RESOURCES MANAGEMENT IN THE UNITED STATES', 'GEOG 540', 2, 'An investigation of the various approaches to water resources geography within the U.S. Explores the disciplines that address water resources management, their tools, and their limitations. Topics include engineering, law, economics, risk assessment, game theory, conflict resolution, and the fine arts. Equivalent course is GEO 525.', ''),
(2949, '3', 'INTERNATIONAL WATER RESOURCES MANAGEMENT', 'GEOG 541', 2, 'An investigation of the various approaches to water resources geography at the international level. Explores the interaction between water science and policy through issues of current \"hydropolitics\" and water resources development. Topics include water quality, dams and development, conflict and cooperation, climate change, and water institutions. Equivalent course is GEO 524.', ''),
(2950, '4', 'PLANNING PRINCIPLES AND PRACTICES FOR RESILIENT COMMUNITIES', 'GEOG 551', 2, 'Applies GIS skills and techniques to determine and analyze future land uses. Determine suitable land uses that incorporate community goals, site constraints and minimize use conflicts. Regulatory and market-based implementation strategies for land uses will also be discussed.', 'Prerequisites: GEOG 360 or 560.A minimum grade of C is required in GEOG 360 and GEOG 560.'),
(2951, '3', 'SUSTAINABLE SITE PLANNING', 'GEOG 552', 2, 'Use of geographic concepts and techniques in site planning to create sustainable management reports for local sites. Inventory of environmental characteristics and human uses, conceptual design for future uses of the site, principles of green infrastructure and sustainable building practices. Local field trip required, transportation fee charged. Equivalent course is GEO 551.', ''),
(2952, '4', 'GISCIENCE I: INTRODUCTION TO GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION SCIENCE', 'GEOG 560', 2, 'Introduction to modern spatial data processing, development, and functions of geographic information systems (GIS); theory, concepts and applications of geographic information science (GIScience). Equivalent course is GEO 565.', ''),
(2953, '4', 'GISCIENCE II: ANALYSIS AND APPLICATIONS', 'GEOG 561', 2, 'Applications-based course. Development and conduct of geospatial analyses using various spatial data structures, techniques and models. Students acquire, clean, integrate, manipulate, visualize and analyze geospatial data through laboratory work. Lec/lab. Equivalent course is GEO 580.', 'Prerequisite: GEOG 560.A minimum grade of C is required in GEOG 560.'),
(2954, '4', 'GISCIENCE III: PROGRAMMING FOR GEOSPATIAL ANALYSIS', 'GEOG 562', 2, 'Introduction to the extension of geographic information systems (GIS) through programming. No prior programming experience is expected. Teaches a pragmatic approach to design and write programs for geospatial analysis. Equivalent course is GEO 578.', 'Prerequisites: GEOG 361 or 561.A minimum grade of C is required in GEOG 361 and GEOG 561.'),
(2955, '3', 'GEOSPATIAL PERSPECTIVES ON INTELLIGENCE, SECURITY, AND ETHICS', 'GEOG 564', 2, 'Applications and implications of geospatial science (GIS, remote sensing, and spatial analysis) in intelligence, human, environmental, and ethical domains. Concepts and practices of ethics in geospatial science, including data access, management, visualization, and decision-making.', 'Prerequisite: GEOG 560.A minimum grade of C is required in GEOG 560.'),
(2956, '4', 'SPATIO-TEMPORAL VARIATION IN ECOLOGY AND EARTH SCIENCE', 'GEOG 565', 2, 'Objectives and techniques of spatial and temporal analysis. Point patterns, geostatistics, spectral analysis, wavelet analysis, interpolation, and mapping. Equivalent course is GEO 541.', ''),
(2957, '4', 'ADVANCED SPATIAL STATISTICS AND GISCIENCE', 'GEOG 566', 2, 'Provides advanced graduate students from a variety of disciplines in earth science and ecology the opportunity to structure and conduct spatio-temporal analyses using available software tools and their own datasets for their graduate research. Equivalent course is GEO 584.', ''),
(2958, '4', 'REMOTE SENSING I: PRINCIPLES AND APPLICATIONS', 'GEOG 580', 2, 'Fundamentals of satellite remote sensing and image analysis. Topics include physical principles of remote sensing from the ultraviolet to the microwave, sensors and sensor technology, and environmental applications of remote sensing through image analysis.', ''),
(2959, '4', 'DIGITAL IMAGE PROCESSING', 'GEOG 581', 2, 'Digital analysis of remote sensor data. Image display enhancement, classification, and rectification principles. Practical experience with an image processing system. Equivalent course is GEO 566.', 'Prerequisite: GEOG 580.A minimum grade of C is required in GEOG 580.'),
(2960, '3', 'FIELD GEOGRAPHY OF OREGON II', 'GEOG 595', 2, 'Designed to introduce students to the widest possible range of topics on all aspects of Oregon geography within a limited time, then turn that experience into a viable research proposal. While physical processes are the primary topic, resource and environmental effects are stressed. Field trip required, transportation fee charged. Equivalent course is GEO 534.', ''),
(2961, '3', 'FIELD RESEARCH IN GEOMORPHOLOGY AND LANDSCAPE ECOLOGY', 'GEOG 596', 2, 'Natural history interpretation of disturbance and recovery processes and management implications in forest-stream landscapes of western Oregon. Course consists of field experience and several seminars. Transportation and lodging fee charged. Equivalent course is GEO 548.', ''),
