(3866, '3', 'MASTER/APPRENTICE STUDY OF A LESS COMMONLY TAUGHT LANGUAGE', 'LING 115', 0, 'LING 114, LING 115, and LING 116 provides context-rich beginning language instruction, in close collaboration with a native speaker, of a language otherwise not taught at OSU. Learners work toward a level of communicative proficiency approaching the intermediate low level in each of the primary skill areas. Four credits of one language are required before moving on to the next course in the sequence. May be repeated for credit for up to three languages. Not for students who have previous proficiency in the target language.', ''),
(3867, '3', '*WESTERN CULTURE STUDY ABROAD', 'LING 208', 0, 'Overseas study of the history and contemporary form of important features of Western culture. Based on at least 10 weeks of studying abroad. CROSSLISTED as ANTH 208/LING 208. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(3868, '4', 'PROJECT MANAGEMENT', 'MGMT 364', 0, 'Covers the tools available to project managers, the human and organizational dimensions in different project environments, some computer applications, cases, and a project.', 'Prerequisites: BA 351, 352 or 352H.A minimum grade of C is required in BA 351, BA 352 and BA 352H.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Business Administration (181)Business Information Systems (183)Management (196)Accounting Information Systems (236)Apparel Design (400)Merchandising Management (416)Pre-Apparel (453)Pre-Interiors (454)Interior Design (458)Supply Chain & Logistics Mgmt (694)Design & Innovation Management (912)'),
(3869, '4', 'CROSS-CULTURAL MANAGEMENT', 'MGMT 446', 0, 'Provides a comprehensive understanding of cross-cultural management issues including leading culturally diverse workforces and managing diversity in the workplace. Students will not only learn theoretical foundations and best practices to address regarding global work practices, but also learn how to transfer and apply the course materials in this course to their', 'Prerequisites: BA 352 or 352H.A minimum grade of C is required in BA 352 and BA 352H.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Management (196) or Organizational Leadership (818).'),
(3870, '4', 'EMPLOYEE RECRUITMENT AND SELECTION', 'MGMT 448', 0, 'Provides an in-depth coverage of best practices pertaining to the process of attracting, selecting, and hiring new employees in modern organizations. Topics that will be emphasized include recruitment tactics, legal issues related to staffing, the criteria organizations use to make hiring decisions, and the strengths and weaknesses of various techniques used to evaluate prospective applicants throughout the selection process. The implications of what we discuss for the organization, the hiring manager, and the job-seeker are considered.', 'Prerequisites: BA 352 or 352H.A minimum grade of C is required in BA 352 and BA 352H.Enrollment limited to students in the Oregon State - Cascades campus.'),
(3871, '4', 'COMPENSATION MANAGEMENT', 'MGMT 449', 0, 'Students will understand and design methods of compensation aimed at motivating and rewarding employee contributions to the organization. Employee contributions may include behavior, skills and goods/services that employees produce as individuals, teams, business units, projects or organizations. Topics include pay strategies and structures, performance measurement and evaluation, and various non-salary incentives.', 'Prerequisite: BA 352.A minimum grade of C is required in BA 352.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.'),
(3872, '4', 'LEADERSHIP', 'MGMT 452', 0, 'In-depth study of leadership research, theory and skills. Emphasis on analysis of organizational leadership situations and application of leadership skills in the workplace.', 'Prerequisites: BA 351, 352 or 352H.A minimum grade of C is required in BA 351, BA 352 and BA 352H.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Management (196), Organizational Leadership (818), Innovation Management (851) or Human Resource Analytics (902).'),
(3873, '4', 'HUMAN RESOURCES MANAGEMENT', 'MGMT 453', 0, 'Personnel administration for line supervisors and managers. Integrates systems approach to understanding government regulation of employment, resolution of workplace personnel problems, and performance-based personnel management.', 'Prerequisites: BA 351, 352 or 352H.A minimum grade of C is required in BA 351, BA 352 and BA 352H.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Management (196)General Business (201)Health Management and Policy (242)Nutrition and Foodservice Sys (261)Construction Engineering Mgt (338)Retail Management (744)Family Business (786)'),
(3874, '4', 'INFLUENCE AND NEGOTIATION', 'MGMT 455', 0, 'Focuses on analysis, skill development and application of management research to real-life organizational influence, persuasion, negotiation and conflict management situations.', 'Prerequisites: BA 352 or 352H.A minimum grade of C is required in BA 352 and BA 352H.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in:Management (196)General Business (201)Supply Chain & Logistics Mgmt (694)Family Business (786)Marketing (799)Professional Sales (817)'),
(3875, '4', 'SUPPLY CHAIN STRATEGY', 'MGMT 457', 0, 'Covers tools and concepts needed to manage the supply chain effectively. Topics include negotiation, purchasing, logistics operations, and applying e-business tools. Emphasis on creating integrated supply chains.', 'Prerequisites: BA 357 or 357H.A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 357 and BA 357H.Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Management (196), General Business (201), Supply Chain & Logistics Mgmt (694) or Retail Management (744).'),
(3876, '4', 'SELECTED TOPICS IN MANAGEMENT: ST/SUPPLY CHAIN MANAGEMENT', 'MGMT 499', 0, 'Examination of the impact of recent advances in management on contemporary business. Topic will vary from term to term.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman, Sophomore or Junior may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Management (196) or Supply Chain & Logistics Mgmt (694).'),
(3877, '4', 'EMPLOYEE RECRUITMENT AND SELECTION', 'MGMT 548', 2, 'Provides an in-depth coverage of best practices pertaining to the process of attracting, selecting, and hiring new employees in modern organizations. Topics that will be emphasized include recruitment tactics, legal issues related to staffing, the criteria organizations use to make hiring decisions, and the strengths and weaknesses of various techniques used to evaluate prospective applicants throughout the selection process. The implications of what we discuss for the organization, the hiring manager, and the job-seeker are considered.', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Human Resource Management (2065).'),
(3878, '4', 'COMPENSATION MANAGEMENT', 'MGMT 549', 2, 'Students will understand and design methods of compensation aimed at motivating and rewarding employee contributions to the organization. Employee contributions may include behavior, skills and goods/services that employees produce as individuals, teams, business units, projects or organizations. Topics include pay strategies and structures, performance measurement and evaluation, and various non-salary incentives.', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Human Resource Management (2065).'),
(3879, '4', 'HUMAN RESOURCES MANAGEMENT', 'MGMT 553', 2, 'Personnel administration for line supervisors and managers. Integrates systems approach to understanding government regulation of employment, resolution of workplace personnel problems, and performance-based personnel management.', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Organizational Leadership (2048), Business Administration (2049), Business Administration (2050) or Human Resource Management (2065).'),
(3880, '4', 'INFLUENCE AND NEGOTIATION', 'MGMT 555', 2, 'Focuses on analysis, skill development and application of management research to real life organizational influence, persuasion, negotiation and conflict management situations.', 'Prerequisite: BA 516.A minimum grade of C is required in BA 516.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Organizational Leadership (2048), Business Administration (2049), Business Administration (2050) or Human Resource Management (2065).'),
(3881, '3', 'MANAGING ETHICS AND CORPORATE SOCIAL RESPONSIBILITY', 'MGMT 559', 2, 'Introduces students to contemporary issues managers face making ethical and socially-responsible decisions in an increasingly competitive, transparent, and global environment. Practical examples and cases, as well as contemporary behavioral ethics research and theory are incorporated throughout the course.', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Business Administration (2050).Professional level students may not enroll.'),
(3882, '3', 'STRATEGIC HUMAN RESOURCE MANAGEMENT', 'MGMT 572', 2, 'Students will learn the theories of human resource management, the legal requirements for human resource practices, and how to create an HR measurement system that aligns with an organization?s strategy.', 'Prerequisite: BA 550.A minimum grade of C- is required in BA 550.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Organizational Leadership (2048), Business Administration (2049), Organizational Leadership (2061) or Human Resource Management (2065).'),
(3883, '3', 'NEGOTIATIONS', 'MGMT 574', 2, 'Students will learn the theories of negotiation and the techniques to develop an effective negotiation style.', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Organizational Leadership (2048), Business Administration (2049), Organizational Leadership (2061) or Human Resource Management (2065).Students in the Oregon State - Corvallis campus may not enroll.'),
(3884, '3', 'INTEGRATIVE CAPSTONE I', 'MGMT 575', 2, 'First course in a two-course sequence spanning the final two quarters of the OLMBA program. Students will conduct an extensive analysis of the student\'s organization, the industry and external environment, the organization\'s competitors, internal organization, and business level strategy.', 'Prerequisite: BA 562.A minimum grade of B is required in BA 562.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Organizational Leadership (2061).'),
(3885, '3', 'INTEGRATIVE CAPSTONE II', 'MGMT 576', 2, 'Second course in a two-course sequence spanning the final two quarters of the OLMBA program. Students start from the final proposal in MGMT 575 and formulate an integrative project plan through the application of multidisciplinary knowledge.', 'Prerequisite: MGMT 575.A minimum grade of B is required in MGMT 575.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Organizational Leadership (2061).'),
(3886, '3', 'ORGANIZATIONAL BEHAVIOR', 'MGMT 650', 2, 'Surveys research on individual differences, psychological states, and team processes related to work motivation, decision-making and performance.', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Business Administration (2050).Enrollment limited to students in a Doctor of Philosophy degree.'),
(3887, '3', 'INTRODUCTION TO INDUSTRIAL AND MANUFACTURING ENGINEERING', 'MFGE 285', 0, 'Introduction to selected topics in industrial and manufacturing engineering, including history and philosophy, product design and manufacturing cycle, integrate role of engineering and business, and multi-objective nature of organizations. Surveys of selected design problems in resource allocation, operations and quality management, and production engineering. CROSSLISTED as IE 285/MFGE 285.', 'Prerequisites: IE 112* or FOR 112*.* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of C is required in IE 112 and FOR 112.Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.Enrollment limited to students in the Pre-Engineering Program college.'),
(3888, '4', 'PRODUCTION ENGINEERING', 'MFGE 336', 0, 'Provides a general understanding of the production engineering function within industry and the means by which to achieve tight tolerances through machining. Geometric dimensioning and tolerancing, fixture and gage design, and fundamentals of metal cutting mechanics are introduced, and their interactions are explored. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisites: (ENGR 213 or 213H) and ENGR 248 and (ENGR 321, 321H, MATS 321 or 321H) and ME 250.A minimum grade of C is required in ENGR 213, ENGR 213H, ENGR 248, ENGR 321, ENGR 321H, MATS 321, MATS 321H and ME 250.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Manufacturing Engineering (317) or Industrial Engineering (323).Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(3889, '4', 'MATERIALS AND MANUFACTURING PROCESSES', 'MFGE 337', 0, 'Introduces mechanical manufacturing methods by which materials are economically shaped into valuable products. The overall goal is to develop an understanding of how the functionality, shape, materials, cost and sustainability of a product influence manufacturing process selection and design. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisites: ((ENGR 321, 321H, MATS 321 or 321H) and ME 250 and MFGE 336).A minimum grade of C is required in ENGR 321, ENGR 321H, MATS 321, MATS 321H, ME 250 and MFGE 336.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Manufacturing Engineering (317) or Industrial Engineering (323).Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(3890, '4', 'LEAN MANUFACTURING SYSTEMS ENGINEERING', 'MFGE 436', 0, 'The planning, evaluation, deployment, and integration of lean manufacturing theory and methods. Examines manufacturing processes/equipment and systems, e.g., planning/control, product design, supply chain resource management. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisites: ENGR 390 or 391.A minimum grade of C is required in ENGR 390 and ENGR 391.Students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore may not enroll.Enrollment is limited to students with a major in Manufacturing Engineering (317) or Industrial Engineering (323).Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(3891, '4', 'COMPUTER CONTROL OF MANUFACTURING PROCESSES', 'MFGE 437', 0, 'Introduces fundamental knowledge in the automation of manufacturing systems and processes. Automated manufacturing system design and operations--computer numerical control (CNC) technology; NC part programming; sensors and actuators, their modeling and dynamic simulation; feedback motion delivery systems design and tuning; programmable logic controls (PLC) for industrial control systems, and path planning for numerical controlled (NC) machinery. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisites: (ME 317, 317H or MFGE 336) and (ENGR 212 or 212H).A minimum grade of C is required in ME 317, ME 317H, MFGE 336, ENGR 212 and ENGR 212H.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Manufacturing Engineering (317), Mechanical Engineering (321), Industrial Engineering (323) or Product Development (833).Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(3892, '1', 'SEMINAR', 'MFGE 507', 2, 'Graded P/N.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(3893, '1', 'SEMINAR: SEM/ ADV MANUFACTURING', 'MFGE 507', 2, 'Graded P/N.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(3894, '1', 'SEMINAR: SEM/ ADVANCED MANUFACTURING', 'MFGE 507', 2, 'Graded P/N.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(3895, '4', 'MICROMANUFACTURING', 'MFGE 531', 2, 'Introduction to microsystem platforms, scaling laws and size effects in micromanufacturing techniques with an emphasis on microchannel arrays, microchannel lamination and micro-scale characterization. Lec/lab.', ''),
(3896, '4', 'LEAN MANUFACTURING SYSTEMS ENGINEERING', 'MFGE 536', 2, 'The planning, evaluation, deployment, and integration of lean manufacturing theory and methods. Examines manufacturing processes/equipment and systems, e.g., planning/control, product design, supply chair resource management. Lec/lab.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(3897, '3', 'ADDITIVE MANUFACTURING', 'MFGE 551', 2, 'Introduces basic principles and process physics for additive manufacturing as compared with subtractive manufacturing. Various processes in AM (extrusion, jetting, photopolymerization, powder bed fusion, direct energy deposition and sheet lamination) and laser AM are discussed. Materials selection in AM (metals, polymers, ceramics and composites), powder metallurgy and metallurgical phenomena in additive manufacturing will be covered.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(3898, '4', 'SPECIAL TOPICS: ST/ SENSOR DSGN FOR MANUFACTUR', 'MFGE 599', 2, '', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(3899, '3', 'SPECIAL TOPICS: ST/COMP METHDS FOR ADV MFG', 'MFGE 599', 2, '', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
