(4223, '4', 'MODERN PRODUCT DESIGN', 'ME 611', 2, 'Modern product development, design and prototyping are covered. Product development and prototyping is examined from a research standpoint in this course. Customer outcomes gathering, functional modeling, product architecture, modern techniques for concept generation and selection are explored. Also covered are recently developed theories and techniques for prototyping. The topics\' place in the overall design process is shown through a product development and prototyping project.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(4224, '4', 'DESIGN UNDER UNCERTAINTY', 'ME 615', 2, 'Tackles the problem of decision making in engineering design. The fundamental challenge faced in making decisions in engineering designs is that they are almost exclusively decisions made under uncertainty. Sources of uncertainty could result from engineering models, experiments conducted, or lack of knowledge of future events. The course will cover three basic topics 1) how do we quantify uncertainty, 2) how do we account for the uncertainty in decision making, and 3) how do we make design selection decisions about products or systems we design.', 'Prerequisite: ME 517.A minimum grade of C is required in ME 517.Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.Enrollment limited to students in the College of Engineering college.'),
(4225, '1', 'ORIENTATION TO MICROBIOLOGY', 'MB 110', 0, 'Introduction of incoming microbiology students to college life with an emphasis on faculties, facilities, services, and curricula in microbiology. Exposure to career opportunities in microbiology. Graded P/N.', 'Enrollment limited to students with a term level of Freshman or Sophomore.'),
(4226, '1 to 16', 'LABORATORY SKILLS', 'MB 201', 0, 'These credits are designed for students who are doing experiential learning in a research laboratory on campus, performing basic laboratory tasks that are not elevated to the level of an independent research project. Graded P/N.', ''),
(4227, '4', '*INTRODUCTORY MICROBIOLOGY', 'MB 230', 0, 'Microbiology as it affects our everyday lives. The impact of microorganisms on health, food/water sanitation, environment, industry, and genetic engineering. Lec/lab. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(4228, '4', '*ALLIED HEALTH MICROBIOLOGY', 'MB 255', 0, 'General properties of cellular microbes and viruses, microbial biochemistry and genetics, pathogenesis and disease, immunity, and microbial infections. Lecture and lab emphasis is on medical microbiology, infectious diseases, and public health. Not intended for biological sciences majors. Lec/lab. CROSSLISTED as BHS 255/MB 255.', ''),
(4229, '1', 'SUCCESS IN MICROBIOLOGY', 'MB 290', 0, 'Science skills, science literacy, ethics, and professional development to build a successful career in Microbiology. Learn the process of research, access and analyze primary literature, evaluate user-generated science content, practice professional skills, and identify and plan for experience-building opportunities such as jobs, research and internships. Sophomore standing or higher.', 'Students with a term level of Freshman may not enroll.'),
(4230, '1 to 16', 'SPECIAL TOPICS: ST/ LABORATORY EXPERIENCE', 'MB 299', 0, 'May be repeated for credit when topic varies.', ''),
(4231, '3', 'GENERAL MICROBIOLOGY', 'MB 302', 0, 'Emphasis on cytology, physiology,  virology, growth and control of growth with coverage of the role of microorganisms in nature, in disease, and as useful tools.', 'Prerequisites: (CH 332 or 335) and (((BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H)) or (BI 204, 205 and 206)).A minimum grade of C- is required in CH 332, CH 335, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213, BI 213H, BI 204, BI 205 and BI 206.'),
(4232, '2', 'GENERAL MICROBIOLOGY LAB: GENERAL MICRO LAB', 'MB 303', 0, 'Development of laboratory techniques; exercises designed to reinforce concepts covered in MB 302. MB 302 is a prereq that may be taken prior to or concurrently with MB 303. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisite: MB 302*.* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of D- is required in MB 302.'),
(4233, '2', 'GENERAL MICROBIOLOGY LABORATORY', 'MB 303', 0, 'Development of laboratory techniques; exercises designed to reinforce concepts covered in MB 302. MB 302 is a prereq that may be taken prior to or concurrently with MB 303. Lec/lab.', 'Prerequisite: MB 302*.* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of D- is required in MB 302.'),
(4234, '3', 'BACTERIAL MOLECULAR GENETICS', 'MB 310', 0, 'Introductory concepts of bacterial molecular genetics. Topics include DNA replication, mutation, DNA repair, DNA recombination, transposons, bacteriophages, genetic manipulation, and gene regulation.', 'Prerequisites: MB 302 and (BB 314 or 314H) and (BB 450 or 490) and (BB 451* or 491*).* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of D- is required in MB 302, BB 314, BB 314H, BB 450, BB 490, BB 451 and BB 491.'),
(4235, '3', '^MOLECULAR MICROBIOLOGY LAB: A WRITING INTENSIVE COURSE', 'MB 311', 0, 'Scientific writing, laboratory notebook composition, experimental design, and laboratory experiments in bacterial molecular biology. (Writing Intensive Course)', 'Prerequisites: (MB 303 or 303H) and MB 310*.* May be taken concurrently.A minimum grade of D- is required in MB 303, MB 303H and MB 310.'),
(4236, '3', 'BACTERIAL PHYSIOLOGY AND METABOLISM', 'MB 312', 0, 'Molecular structure and function, macromolecular assembly, energy production and use, and cellular growth.', 'Prerequisites: MB 310 and BB 451.A minimum grade of D- is required in MB 310 and BB 451.'),
(4237, '3', 'AQUATIC MICROBIOLOGY', 'MB 314', 0, 'A survey of the diversity, ecology, and physiology of microbes in aquatic systems, with emphasis on their roles in food webs, chemical cycling, and human health. Provides the background knowledge and quantitative/analytical skills necessary to interpret and critique current and historical research in the fields of general aquatic microbiology.', 'Prerequisites: (CH 231, 231H or 121) and (CH 232, 232H or 122) and (CH 233, 233H or 123).A minimum grade of D- is required in CH 231, CH 231H, CH 121, CH 232, CH 232H, CH 122, CH 233, CH 233H and CH 123.'),
(4238, '4', 'HUMAN BACTERIOLOGY', 'MB 320', 0, 'Properties of bacteria, their biology, pathogenesis and concern to society. Emphasis on the role of bacteria in human health and disease. CROSSLISTED as BHS 320/MB 320.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 204, 205 and 206) or ((BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and (BI 213 or 213H)).A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 204, BI 205, BI 206, BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213 and BI 213H.'),
(4239, '3', '*DISEASE AND SOCIETY', 'MB 330', 0, 'Infectious disease has many effects on the development of society, and likewise, human interactions affect the development of disease. The course examines these interactions with a focus on the role of race, class, and economic status in the development of epidemics. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(4240, '4', 'HUMAN VIROLOGY', 'MB 340', 0, 'Properties of viruses, their biology, pathogenesis and concern to society. Emphasis on viruses causing human disease. CROSSLISTED as BHS 340/MB 340.', 'Prerequisites: (BI 204, 205 and 206) or (BI 211, 212 and 213).A minimum grade of C- is required in BI 204, BI 205, BI 206, BI 211, BI 212 and BI 213.'),
(4241, '3', '^EMERGING INFECTIOUS DISEASES AND EPIDEMICS', 'MB 385', 0, 'Emerging and reemerging infectious disease is a contemporary global issue of great concern. To understand and evaluate the issue, the course covers germ theory, disease history and ecology, microbial pathogenesis and the immune response, historic plagues, and the biological, environmental, population and social changes that contribute to disease emergence. (Writing Intensive Course)', 'Prerequisites: (BI 211 or 211H) and (BI 212 or 212H) and BI 213 or (BI 213H).A minimum grade of D- is required in BI 211, BI 211H, BI 212, BI 212H, BI 213 and BI 213H.'),
