(6154, '3', 'APPLIED SURVIVAL ANALYSIS', 'ST 525', 2, 'Statistical methods for analyzing survival data or time-to-event data, which may be censored and/or truncated. Specific topics can vary term to term, and could include Kaplan-Meier estimator; K-sample hypothesis tests for survival data; Accelerated failure time model; Cox proportional hazard regression model.', 'Prerequisites: ST 516, 517 and 518.A minimum grade of C is required in ST 516, ST 517 and ST 518.'),
(6155, '3', 'SAMPLING METHODS', 'ST 531', 2, 'Estimation of means, totals and proportions; sampling designs including simple random, stratified, cluster, systematic, multistage and double sampling; ratio and regression estimators; sources of errors in surveys; capture-recapture methods.', ''),
(6156, '3', 'DATA VISUALIZATION', 'ST 537', 2, 'Perceptual principles for displaying data; critique and improvement of data visualizations; use of color in visualization; principles of tidy data; strategies for data exploration; select special topics.', 'Prerequisites: ST 512, 517 or 552.A minimum grade of C is required in ST 512, ST 517 and ST 552.'),
(6157, '3', 'MODERN STATISTICAL METHODS FOR LARGE AND COMPLEX DATA SETS', 'ST 538', 2, 'Provides students with the tools and experience to analyze big and messy data and work effectively in a data science team. Covers the tools to handle big data and answer statistical questions based on the data. Includes three big data analysis projects that students work on in groups. Focuses on proper use of modern data analysis techniques related to regression, classification and clustering for data coming from a variety of application fields. R will be the lingua franca.', 'Prerequisites: ST 512, 517, 552 or 412.A minimum grade of C is required in ST 512, ST 517, ST 552 and ST 412.'),
(6158, '3', 'SURVEY METHODS', 'ST 539', 2, 'Survey design, data collection and analysis, general methodology.', ''),
(6159, '4', 'PROBABILITY, COMPUTING, AND SIMULATION IN STATISTICS', 'ST 541', 2, 'Review of probability, including univariate distributions and limit theorems. Random-number generation and simulation of statistical distributions. Bootstrap estimates of standard error. Variance reduction techniques. Emphasis on the use of computation in statistics using the S-Plus or MATLAB programming language. Lec/lab.', ''),
(6160, '3', 'APPLIED STOCHASTIC MODELS', 'ST 543', 2, 'Development of stochastic models commonly arising in statistics and operations research, such as Poisson processes, birth-and-death processes, discrete-time and continuous-time Markov chains, renewal and Markov renewal processes. Analysis of stochastic models by simulation and other computational techniques.', ''),
(6161, '4', 'STATISTICAL METHODS', 'ST 551', 2, 'Properties of t, chi-square and F tests; randomized experiments; sampling distributions and standard errors of estimators, delta method, comparison of several groups of measurements; two-way tables of measurements.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(6162, '3', 'ADVANCED EXPERIMENTAL DESIGN', 'ST 555', 2, 'Designs leading to mixed models including split plots, repeated measures, crossovers and incomplete blocks. Introduction to experimental design in industry including confounding, fractional factorials and response surface methodology. Analysis of unbalanced data.', 'Prerequisite: ST 553.A minimum grade of C is required in ST 553.'),
(6163, '3', 'MULTIVARIATE ANALYTICS', 'ST 558', 2, 'Basics of matrix algebra, principal components analysis, cluster analysis, factor analysis, multidimensional scaling.', 'Prerequisite: ST 518.A minimum grade of C- is required in ST 518.'),
(6164, '3', 'BAYESIAN STATISTICS', 'ST 559', 2, 'Bayesian statistics for data analysis. Characterizations of probability; comparative (Bayesian versus frequentist) inference; prior, posterior and predictive distributions; hierarchical modeling. Computational methods include Markov Chain Monte Carlo for posterior simulation.', ''),
(6165, '4', 'THEORY OF STATISTICS', 'ST 561', 2, 'Distributions of functions of random variables, joint and conditional distributions, sampling distributions, convergence concepts, order statistics. Lec/rec.', ''),
(6166, '3', 'TIME SERIES', 'ST 565', 2, 'Analysis of serially correlated data in both time and frequency domains. Autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation functions, autoregressive integrated moving average models, model building, forecasting; filtering, smoothing, spectral analysis, frequency response studies, Offered winter term in even years.', ''),
(6167, '3', 'TIME SERIES ANALYTICS', 'ST 566', 2, 'Focuses on statistical and analytical tools for analyzing data that are observed sequentially over time. Specific topics can vary term to term, and could include methods for exploratory time series analysis, linear time series models (ARMA, ARIMA), forecasting, spectral analysis and state-space models. The focus will be on applied problems, though some mathematical statistics is necessary for a solid understanding of the statistical issues. This course is designed for students in Data Analytics MS and Certificate programs.', 'Prerequisites: ST 516, 517 and 518.A minimum grade of C is required in ST 516, ST 517 and ST 518.Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(6168, '3', 'STATISTICAL METHODS FOR GENOMICS RESEARCH', 'ST 592', 2, 'Lectures include an overview of statistical methods commonly applied in genomics research. Specific methods can vary term to term, and could include cluster analysis, decision trees, dimension reduction tools, regression models, multiple testing adjustment, variable selection methods, etc. Journal clubs include team-based review and presentations of landmark papers in both statistical methodology and genomics research. Research experience includes whole-term collaboration between students from statistics and other disciplines on real projects.', 'Enrollment limited to students in the Dist. Degree Corvallis Student campus.'),
(6169, '3', 'CAPSTONE PROJECT', 'ST 595', 2, 'Provides an opportunity for students to integrate and apply the analytics skills learned in MS in Data Analytics program to solve real-world problems and to interpret and communicate their results. Student teams will engage in the entire process of solving data science projects in realistic settings, from placing the problem into appropriate statistical framework to applying suitable analytic methods to the problem. Problem solving, written and oral communication skills will be emphasized.', 'Prerequisites: ST 516, 517, 518 and 558.A minimum grade of C is required in ST 516, ST 517, ST 518 and ST 558.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Data Analytics (6160).Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.Enrollment limited to students in the Dist. Degree Corvallis Student campus.'),
(6170, '3', 'SPECIAL TOPICS: ST/ RISK & UNCERTAINTY', 'ST 599', 2, 'May be repeated for credit when topic varies.', ''),
(6171, '2', 'SPECIAL TOPICS: ST/DATA PROGRAMMING IN R', 'ST 599', 2, 'May be repeated for credit when topic varies.', ''),
(6172, '1 to 16', 'RESEARCH', 'ST 601', 2, '', ''),
(6173, '1 to 16', 'THESIS', 'ST 603', 2, '', ''),
(6174, '1 to 16', 'PROJECTS', 'ST 606', 2, 'Section 1:  Projects; Section 2:  Teaching Experience, graded P/N; Section 3:  Directed Work, graded P/N.', ''),
(6175, '3', 'GENERALIZED REGRESSION MODELS', 'ST 623', 2, 'Maximum likelihood analysis for frequency data; regression-type models for binomial and Poisson data; iterative weighted least squares and maximum likelihood; analysis of deviance and residuals; over-dispersion and quasilikelihood models; log-linear models for multidimensional contingency tables.', 'Prerequisites: ST 553 and 563.A minimum grade of C is required in ST 553 and ST 563.'),
(6176, '3', 'SURVIVAL ANALYSIS', 'ST 625', 2, 'Prepares students to understand and analyze survival data. Concepts to be discussed include: hazard function (failure rate function); nonparametric likelihood; empirical processes; empirical distribution function; censoring (mostly right independent censoring); Kaplan-Meier estimator; Bias of the KM estimator; Cox proportional hazards model; Accelerated Failure Time Model; Partial Likelihood; log-rank test.', 'Prerequisites: ST 553 or 563.A minimum grade of C is required in ST 553 and ST 563.'),
(6177, '3', 'LINEAR MODEL THEORY', 'ST 651', 2, 'Least squares estimation, best linear unbiased estimation, parameterizations, multivariate normal distributions, distributions of quadratic forms, testing linear hypotheses, simultaneous confidence intervals. Offered alternate years.', ''),
(6178, '4', '*INTRODUCTION TO ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE AND SUSTAINABILITY', 'SUS 102', 0, 'An introduction to the science behind critical environmental issues and the biological basis of creating and maintaining sustainable ecosystems. Focus on such questions as: how do we decide what to believe about environmental issues? How do we quantify, restore, and value biodiversity? What is valid science in the global warming debate? Lec/lab. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(6179, '4', '*INTRODUCTION TO CLIMATE CHANGE', 'SUS 103', 0, 'An introduction to the principles of climate change science with an emphasis on the empirical evidence for climate change. Students will learn critical thinking skills to assess such questions as: How do we determine the processes controlling global warming? How do we predict trends in climate change? How do we calculate and understand uncertainty in these predictions? What is valid science in the global warming debate? Lec/lab. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(6180, '4', '*SUSTAINABILITY ASSESSMENT', 'SUS 304', 0, 'Explores theories and application of sustainability assessment techniques and analysis methods. Practical application of globally recognized assessment protocol, including checklists, footprinting, life-cycle analysis and the indicators used to conduct these analyses. Emphasis on ecological and social indicators, although economic indicators are explored. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(6181, '3', '^AG AND ENVIRONMENTAL PREDICAMENTS: A CASE STUDY APPROACH', 'SUS 325', 0, 'Analyze controversial agricultural and environmental issues, synthesize information from diverse sources, and apply scientific knowledge to recommend specific courses of action to solve real world problems. Develop oral and written communication skills through individual and group work. (Writing Intensive Course)', ''),
(6182, '3', '*SUSTAINABILITY, JUSTICE, AND ENGAGEMENT', 'SUS 331', 0, 'Many sustainability crises are local, and the people most impacted tend to be groups already experiencing difference, lack of power, and discrimination. Transformational responses led by those most affected will be examined -- responses that address the environmental problem while also building social and economic power for those affected. The tools and tactics used to achieve positive changes will be analyzed. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(6183, '4', '*SUSTAINABLE COMMUNITIES', 'SUS 350', 0, 'Introduction to the concept of sustainable communities from a multidisciplinary perspective. Instructors from a broad array of disciplines and professions. Development of holistic thinking skills and innovative solutions to complex problems. (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(6184, '1 to 16', 'RESEARCH', 'SUS 401', 0, '', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Sustainability (870) or Sustainability (871).'),
(6185, '1 to 16', 'INTERNSHIP', 'SUS 410', 0, '', 'Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Sustainability (870) or Sustainability (871).'),
(6186, '3', 'SOCIAL DIMENSIONS OF SUSTAINABILITY', 'SUS 420', 0, 'Focuses on the social aspects of sustainability, including how the environment, the economy, social life interact to create the world we live in. Explores how social institutions (school, government, business, family) contribute to sustainability and promote or discourage social and environmental justice at local and global scales. Also offered at OSU-Cascades and via Ecampus.', ''),
(6187, '2', 'INDEPENDENT PROJECT IN NATURAL RESOURCE SUSTAINABILITY', 'SNR 506', 2, 'Students identify, pose, frame, and analyze the various components of an important natural resource sustainability problem within their country, region, or organization and, at the end of term, present a workplan for its resolution. Oral and written reports are expected. Graded P/N.', 'Prerequisite: SNR 511.A minimum grade of C is required in SNR 511.Enrollment is limited to students with a program in Sustainable Natural Resources (CG01).Enrollment is limited to Graduate or Non-Degree / Credential level students.'),
(6188, '1', 'SUSTAINABLE NATURAL RESOURCE DEVELOPMENT', 'SNR 511', 2, 'Using readings, class discussions, and field trips, we introduce the program sessions and pedagogical methods, familiarize students with basic working definitions of sustainability, and build capacity to work as group on a common project.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate or Non-Degree / Credential level students.'),
(6189, '3', 'SOCIAL ASPECTS OF SUSTAINABLE NATURAL RESOURCES', 'SNR 520', 2, 'Using readings, personal experiences, and class discussions, students explore five principles of socially sustainable natural resource management, and review the role they play in creating natural resource-based sustainable communities.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate or Non-Degree / Credential level students.'),
(6190, '3', 'ECONOMICS OF SUSTAINABLE NATURAL RESOURCE MANAGEMENT', 'SNR 521', 2, 'Focuses on the sources of market failure, the means of correcting market failure, and the real-world examples of making progress toward sustainable resource use by means of market mechanisms.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate or Non-Degree / Credential level students.'),
(6191, '3', 'BASIC BELIEFS AND ETHICS IN NATURAL RESOURCES', 'SNR 522', 2, 'Examines basic philosophies and ethical systems in American forestry, including Pinchot\'s agricultural/utilitarian approach and Leopold\'s biotic/ecological model, compares them to contemporary public attitudes and considers their implications for sustainability.', ''),
(6192, '3', 'ECOLOGICAL PRINCIPLES OF SUSTAINABLE NATURAL RESOURCES', 'SNR 530', 2, 'Focus an ecological sustainability and ecological concepts and principles, with examples drawn from forests and arid lands. Exploration of global ecosystems, ecological processes and services, factors that create and maintain diversity, ecosystem health and integrity. Principles for sustainable natural resource management and use.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate or Non-Degree / Credential level students.'),
(6193, '2', 'PLANNING AGROFORESTRY PROJECTS', 'SNR 532', 2, 'Develop basic understanding and appreciation of agroforestry concepts, systems, technologies and practices as used and applied in tropical and temperate zones of the world.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(6194, '3', 'NONTIMBER FOREST PRODUCTS: AN INTERDISCIPLINARY INTRODUCTION', 'SNR 533', 2, 'Interdisciplinary introduction to the culture, history, economy, ecology, policy and management of nontimber forest products (NTFP), e.g., wild foods, medicines, floral greens, craft material and landscaping species. Includes domestic public and private forest and international case studies.', ''),
(6195, '3', 'SUSTAINABLE MANAGEMENT OF AQUATIC AND RIPARIAN RESOURCES', 'SNR 535', 2, 'Explores integrated strategies for sustainable management of watersheds, estuaries, coastal zones, and aquatic resources. Special emphasis given to links between land uses and aquatic environments. Part of the 18-credit Sustainable Natural Resources (SNR) Graduate Certificate; also open to other graduate students.', ''),
(6196, '3', 'GLOBAL ENVIRONMENTAL CHANGE', 'SNR 540', 2, 'Explore biophysical and social sciences that underlie contemporary global change issues: global biogeochemical cycles, climate system, climate change, threats to biodiversity; human dimensions of climate change, globalization, land cover and land use change, global environmental governance and management tools.', 'Enrollment is limited to Graduate level students.'),
(6197, '1', 'PLAYREADING', 'TA 144', 0, 'Reading/discussion/examination of plays from world theatre of past and present from the perspective of production and theatre history.', ''),
(6198, '3', '*INTRODUCTION TO THE THEATRE', 'TA 147', 0, 'Origins, history, nature, elements, and style of theatre production; function of artists and craftspersons of the theatre. (FA) (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(6199, '3', 'VISUAL PRINCIPLES OF THEATRE', 'TA 242', 0, 'An introduction to visual creativity, creative thinking, and visual problem solving as applied to theatre arts as a whole, and to scene and costume design. (FA)', ''),
(6200, '3', 'PRINCIPLES OF COSTUMING FOR THE STAGE', 'TA 243', 0, 'Principles and techniques of costume construction; practical application in the costume shop on theatre production.', ''),
(6201, '3', 'SCENE CRAFTS', 'TA 244', 0, 'Constructing scenery and stage properties; practical experience in backstage procedures and scene painting. Lec/lab. (FA)', ''),
(6202, '3', 'STAGE MAKEUP', 'TA 247', 0, 'Basic principles and theory with laboratory experience in most-used applications of theatrical makeup.', ''),
(6203, '3', 'FUNDAMENTALS OF ACTING I', 'TA 248', 0, 'Examination of basic principles and techniques of acting. Exploration of relaxation/focus, personal vocal/physical awareness, the actor\'s craft, and the performance process. (FA)', ''),
(6204, '3', 'FUNDAMENTALS OF ACTING II', 'TA 249', 0, 'Continued work in the basic principles and techniques of acting. Emphasis on improvisation, character analysis, and creation, the balance between truth and technique.', 'Prerequisite: TA 248.A minimum grade of D- is required in TA 248.'),
(6205, '1 to 3', 'WORKSHOP: THEATRE ARTS', 'TA 250', 0, 'Practical experience in performance, technical theatre, or design. Maximum for 6 credits may be applied toward graduation.', ''),
(6206, '3', '*HISTORY OF THE THEATRE', 'TA 330', 0, 'The rise and development of the composite arts of the theatre in their cultural and social context. Origins to 1500. Offered alternate years. (H) (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
(6207, '3', 'PLAYSCRIPT ANALYSIS', 'TA 344', 0, 'Study of major approaches to playscript analysis and detailed application of these systems to the theatrical production process. (H)', 'Prerequisite: TA 147.A minimum grade of D- is required in TA 147.'),
(6208, '3', 'SCENE AND STAGE DESIGN', 'TA 346', 0, 'Designs for stage productions including elements of color, mass, line, and lighting for various types of theatre architecture and plays. Offered alternate years.', ''),
(6209, '3', 'ADVANCED ACTING: STYLES', 'TA 349', 0, 'Discussion, research, rehearsal, performance, and criticism of scenes from a range of period and genre styles. Offered alternate years.', 'Prerequisite: TA 248.A minimum grade of D- is required in TA 248.'),
(6210, '1 to 3', 'WORKSHOP: THEATRE ARTS', 'TA 350', 0, 'Advanced work in acting, directing or technical theatre in dramatic productions; laboratory experience. Maximum of 6 credits may be applied toward graduation.', ''),
(6211, '3', 'FUNDS PLAY DIRECTION', 'TA 354', 0, 'History, theories and techniques of stage direction. Script analysis, study of the audience, staging, working with actors and designers, the production process. Emphasis on practical exploration and application. Offered alternate years.', ''),
(6212, '3', '*MULTICULTURAL AMERICAN THEATRE', 'TA 360', 0, 'Examines the rich panorama of multicultural-American theatre (e.g., African-American, gay and lesbian, Hispanic, Asian American). (H) (Bacc Core Course)', ''),
